<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France Finalizes Aerospace Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French finance ministry has finalized the  
details of a proposed merger between the government-controlled 
aerospace company Aerospatiale and Matra Hautes Technologies, a 
unit of privately-owned Lagardere. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry, in an announcement late Monday, said that a  
planned 20 percent public offering in the merged group would take 
place in the first half of this year, market conditions permitting. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the merger deal, Lagardere will pay the government up to  
two billion francs (about $357 million) for a 33 percent stake in 
the Aerospatiale. The French government will own less than 50 
percent of the new company, but it will still be the largest 
shareholder. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the merger and decline in government ownership  
makes good commercial sense, and may boost the process of European 
defense sector restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are very complementary operations,'' said Antoine Nodet,  
analyst at the Paris brokerage Pinatton. ``The most obvious is in 
missiles, but they are a good match in other activities as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	European aerospace restructuring is expected to continue.  
</P>
<P>
	Germany's DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG and France's Thomson-CSF  
are seen as the next likely movers after British Aerospace PLC's 
takeover earlier this year of General Electric PLC's Marconi 
division. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
