<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Services Deal Starts Mar. 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Nations representing more than 90 percent of the  
world's financial services market agreed Monday that a 
multitrillion-dollar global trade accord should start March 1. 
</P>
<P>
	A key panel of the World Trade Organization decided that the  
financial services agreement, which opens banking, insurance and 
securities markets to international competition, should take effect 
even though 18 countries still have to ratify it. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 52 governments have so far ratified the accord. The 18  
remaining countries have been given until the end of June to 
complete the work which will allow them to join in. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the major trading nations who have come into line are the  
United States, Japan and the countries of the European Union, 
except for Luxembourg which still has to ratify the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade officials welcomed the decision and said they were  
confident the other countries ``will come on board as quickly as 
their procedures allow them to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The officials, who briefed reporters on condition of anonymity,  
said it is difficult to say how much trade is covered by the 
agreement. When the accord was agreed in December 1997, officials 
estimated there were $1.2 trillion worth of foreign-exchange deals 
done daily. They put total world banking assets at $20 trillion and 
insurance premiums at $2 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
	When the accord was agreed after 15 years of work it was greeted  
by supporters of the WTO as a major step forward in promoting 
worldwide free trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The financial sector worldwide has grown considerably in the  
past 30 years, with jobs in that area representing up to 5 percent 
of total world employment, according to WTO figures. 
</P>
<P>
	United States and European financial services companies  
particularly hope to benefit from freer access to the Asian market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
