<DOCNO> APW19990215.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 15:14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rams Sign Free Agent QB Trent Green </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Rams signed free agent  
quarterback Trent Green to a four-year, $16.5 million contract 
Monday, spelling the end of the Tony Banks era. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Dick Vermeil made it clear at a news conference that Green  
was being brought in as the starter. The Rams have made a 
qualifying offer to Banks, a restricted free agent, and likely will 
sign him and trade him. 
</P>
<P>
	After the season, Vermeil said he wanted another quarterback to  
compete with Banks, the starter the last 3 1/2 seasons. He was forced 
to change his mind once he surveyed the potential backup candidates 
and the likely cost. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams were attempting to notify Banks, who is on a Caribbean  
cruise, and give him the news that it's all but a certainty that he 
won't be back next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all do what we have to do,'' Vermeil said. ``I don't mind  
listening to the top people I have around me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe Tony Banks will be a starting quarterback and a very  
successful playoff quarterback,'' Vermeil said. ``It just doesn't 
look like it'll end up being here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vermeil said that Kurt Warner, the third-stringer last season  
and one of the five players exposed for the Cleveland Browns' 
expansion draft, is the backup. 
</P>
<P>
	The assurance that Green would be handed the job closed the deal  
for the Rams, who won a bidding war to lure him away from the 
Washington Redskins. It also helped that the Rams' offensive 
coordinator, Mike Martz, was the Redskins' quarterbacks coach the 
last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to know where I stood and he made it very clear to  
me,'' Green said. ``If there were opportunities out there to be the 
starter and not worry about competition, obviously that brings 
something to the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Green signing came a day after the Rams, who promised to be  
active in the free agency period that began Friday, signed 
offensive guard Adam Timmerman to a five-year, $18.7 million 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Green, 29, started the 1998 season as an unheralded  
third-stringer for Washington, but ended up starting 14 games, 
completing 278 of 509 passes for 3,441 yards and 23 touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The Redskins struggled in the first half of the season, but went  
6-3 over the final nine weeks to finish 7-9. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis had been interested in Rich Gannon, the former Kansas  
City Chiefs quarterback who signed with the Oakland Raiders on 
Monday. Former Raiders quarterback Jeff George had also been 
scheduled to visit Rams Park on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rams may not be done shopping just yet. Atlanta safety Devin  
Bush was in for a visit Monday and others scheduled are Cincinnati 
safety Sam Shade and Pittsburgh wide receiver Charles Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good place to play,'' Bush said. ``They're going to be  
headed for good things. They're really committed to turning this 
thing around.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
