<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Hoop Poll Top 3 Remain Same </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Tennessee, Purdue and Louisiana Tech remained the top three  
teams today in The Associated Press women's basketball poll, which 
underwent considerable shuffling through the rest of the list. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven teams from the Top 25 lost during the past week, but  
seven were beaten by other ranked teams and no one dropped from the 
poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee received 40 of 41 first-place votes to hold the No. 1  
spot for the sixth consecutive week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lady Vols (23-1) had 1,024 points from a national media  
panel after surviving a tough game with Auburn. Tennessee overcame 
33 percent shooting in the second half to beat the Tigers 71-63 at 
Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (23-1), which had 981 points, also had a close call,  
beating Penn State 76-74 in overtime on the road before routing 
Ohio State at home. Louisiana Tech (20-2) beat a Top 25 team, 
Florida International, on the road and received 947 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado State (26-1) moved up one spot to fourth and was  
followed by Old Dominion, Connecticut, Rutgers, Duke, Notre Dame 
and Virginia Tech, which made the Top 10 for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Dominion jumped three places to its highest ranking of the  
season after beating Connecticut, which dropped two spots. Rutgers 
climbed two places following a victory over Notre Dame, which went 
from sixth to ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 7 ranking was the highest for Rutgers since it was sixth  
the week of Jan. 14, 1991. Duke fell one spot to eighth after its 
first Atlantic Coast Conference loss, 80-75 at Clemson. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Tech climbed two places to 11th, North Carolina was 12th,  
UCLA 13th and Clemson and Georgia were tied for 14th. Georgia fell 
four places after losing to unranked Vanderbilt. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State was 16th, followed by Virginia, Oregon, Iowa State  
and UC Santa Barbara. Kansas, Auburn, Florida International, LSU 
and Alabama held the five final spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn also lost to Alabama last week and fell five places for  
the biggest drop in the poll. Clemson's move from 19th to 14th and 
Oregon's from 23rd to 18th were the biggest jumps. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemson beat Georgia Tech by 28 before knocking off Duke, while  
Oregon defeated Washington State and Washington to pull into a 
first-place tie with UCLA in the Pac-10. 
</P>
<P>
	A loss at unranked Kansas State sent Iowa State from 16th to  
19th. The Cyclones rebounded to make a school-record 16 3-pointers 
in a victory over Colorado at home. 
</P>
<P>
	LSU beat Texas-Pan American and South Carolina, but a 25-point  
loss to unranked Arkansas dropped the Lady Tigers from 20th to 
23rd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
