<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fleisher Now a Force on Senior Tour  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Two in a row on the Senior Tour, Fleisher's first    	
</P>
<P>
	SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) -- Move over Arnold Palmer, Jack Nicklaus,  
Gary Player and George Archer. Bruce Fleisher has arrived on the 
Senior Tour in a big way. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmer, Nicklaus, Player and Archer each won the first event  
they played upon entering the PGA's 50-and-over circuit. Fleisher 
joined them just last week by winning in Key Biscayne, Fla., in his 
Senior Tour debut, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday, though, Fleisher went that hallowed company one better.  
</P>
<P>
	He became the first player to win his first two events on the  
Senior PGA Tour when he captured the American Express Invitational. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher performed the feat by shooting a final round  
3-under-par 69, finishing with a three-shot lead over Larry Nelson, 
who closed with a 67. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no expectations of this,'' a gleeful Fleisher gushed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, I tried to prepare for this. But very few guys -- I'm  
thinking Hale Irwin or Jack Nicklaus -- really believe how good they 
are and can look in the mirror and know they can win. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a journeyman and made a living. This is really  
special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how special?  
</P>
<P>
	Well, Fleisher earned $180,000, the largest check of his pro  
career. That boosted his senior winnings to $330,000. 
</P>
<P>
	All that after just one single victory in more than 400 PGA Tour  
starts over 29 years. His total earnings for all those years on the 
regular circuit? Just $1,695,111. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Fleisher easily protected the three-shot lead he  
carried into the final round, touring the Tournament Players Club 
at Prestancia with a four-birdie, one-bogey round, finishing the 
54-hole event with a 13-under total of 203. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleisher never looked back after hitting a 7-iron to 5 feet for  
a birdie at the 416-yard, par-4 third hole. 
</P>
<P>
	``That sort of got me kick-started,'' he said. ``I had a cushion  
of three or four shots most of the day. Actually, I felt pretty 
good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His sole bogey of the day came on the 17th hole, by which time  
he had built a four-shot lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Third was Walter Hall, who had a 66 on Sunday, finishing at 207.  
Tom Wargo had a 72-209 to finish fourth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
