<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Warns Iraq on Threat  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said  
today the U.S. ``response would be swift and sure'' if Iraq 
attacked the Turkish base American planes are using to patrol Iraqi 
skies. Albright is with President Clinton on his trip to Mexico. 
Iraqi vice president Taha Yassin Ramadan had said Iraq will attack 
the Incirlik base if American jets keep patrollng over Iraq. U.S. 
warplanes today fired on Iraqi defense sites in northern Iraq, the 
Defense Department said in Washington. It said the planes returned 
safely to Incirlik. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton At Mexico Summit  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- President Clinton offered a strong hint  
today that he will certify Mexico as a reliable ally in the 
struggle against drugs, saying cooperation ``has clearly improved'' 
under President Ernesto Zedillo. Despite Mexico's disappointing 
record on extraditions and a drop last year in cocaine and heroin 
seizures, Clinton found positive things to say about Mexico's 
efforts. He welcomed a plan announced two weeks ago to invest up to 
$500 million in a new anti-drug initiative and declared, ``The 
United States is ready to do all we can to support you.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Optimistic on Presidency  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- President Clinton today said ``everything  
will be fine'' in post-impeachment politics if Republicans and 
Democrats put aside bitter differences. Clinton spoke with 
reporters at talks with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo. He also 
fueled speculation that his wife, Hillary, might run for a U.S. 
Senate seat from New York. ``She would be terrific,'' Clinton said. 
He quickly added that she has not made a decision and that he would 
enthusiastically support whatever she does. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Nixon Aide Ehrlichman Dies  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- John Ehrlichman, 73, President Nixon's domestic  
affairs adviser who was imprisoned for 18 months for the Watergate 
conspiracy, died yesterday of natural causes at his home in 
Atlanta. He had suffered from diabetes, his son said. Ehrlichman 
resigned from his White House post in 1973. He was convicted two 
years later for obstruction of justice, conspiracy and perjury in 
the attempted cover-up of the burglary of the Democratic National 
Committee offices. 

</P>
<P>
	American Resumes Most Flights  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Most of American Airlines' flights took off as  
scheduled today as negotiations resumed between the company and its 
pilot union on the integration of recently purchased Reno Air. 
American's parent company, AMR Corp., and the Allied Pilots 
Association headed back to the table in virtually the same place 
they were 10 days ago before pilots began calling in sick and 
refusing overtime, canceling thousands of flights and delaying 
travel for more than a half-million passengers. About 800 of 
American's 9,400 pilots were still listed as sick today. 

</P>
<P>
	Serbs May Compromise on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Serbia is willing to make major compromises and  
grant rival ethnic Albanians broad self-rule, but it adamantly 
opposes having NATO troops police a Kosovo agreement, the 
republic's president said today. For the first time since a Kosovo 
peace conference started Feb. 6, Milan Milutinovic indicated Serbs 
were willing to drop most demands that have stalled the talks -- 
with the exception of NATO peacekeeping troops. Milutinovic told 
The Associated Press that abandoning NATO's demands for a 
peacekeeping force was a ``precondition'' for a deal. 

</P>
<P>
	Increase Seen in Seat Belt Use  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After being stalled for years, the percentage  
of Americans wearing seat belts increased in 1998 -- the same year 
police organizations started widespread campaigns to enforce seat 
belt laws. The national percentage jumped from 62.2 percent to 65.1 
percent around the Memorial Day holiday, and again from 69.6 
percent to 70.1 percent around the Thanksgiving holiday, said the 
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration in figures the 
agency was releasing tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Reggie White Retires From Football  
</P>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Defensive end Reggie White of the Green  
Bay Packers retired today. The team said he turned in his 
retirement letter to general manager Ron Wolf. White, 37, the NFL's 
career sacks leader, had 16 sacks and was the Defensive Player of 
the Year in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	Duke Stays No. 1 in AP Hoops Poll  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Duke (25-1), Connecticut (22-1) and Auburn  
(24-1) held onto the top three spots today in the AP men's college 
basketball poll. Michigan State moved up one spot to fourth. 
Maryland and Kentucky each jumped two places to fifth and sixth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  


</P>
