<HEADLINE> Tripp Says Lewinsky Was Suicidal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Linda Tripp said Monday night that Monica  
Lewinsky became suicidal out of fear that President Clinton would 
learn that the former White House intern had confided their 
relationship to friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Mrs. Tripp said that Ms.  
Lewinsky was so upset about being treated badly by the president 
that she tracked down Mrs. Tripp and bombarded her with phone calls 
while she was trying to deal with the death of several close family 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to explain to my (then teen-age) children'' about Ms.  
Lewinsky's relationship with the president ``because of the 
incessant phone calls'' from the former intern during the Christmas 
holiday in 1996, Mrs. Tripp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp said Ms. Lewinsky was ``not suicidal'' due to Clinton  
``dumping her'' but because of her ``biggest fear that he would 
find out she shared her story with somebody else. That was part of 
the suicide threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She revealed that she is ``seriously considering'' writing a  
book about her experiences, a project she said she abandoned in 
1996 because she was afraid of losing her job. That book 
contemplated before the Lewinsky scandal, would have dealt with her 
tenure as a White House aide in the early years of the Clinton 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what I'm seeing, the truth is just never going to get out  
there, so to the extent that I may decide to let the truth come out 
I may show what really happened,'' said Mrs. Tripp when asked about 
her plans for a book now. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether New York book agent Luciane Goldberg would be  
representing her, Mrs. Tripp laughed and said, ``I don't know. She 
may not want me.'' Mrs. Goldberg first suggested that Mrs. Tripp 
tape her phone calls with Ms. Lewinsky in order to document the 
relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp also criticized Ms. Lewinsky's mother, Marcia Lewis,  
for taking the view that her daughter's relationship with the 
president ``was OK; more than OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Depicting herself as an older authority figure for Ms. Lewinsky,  
Mrs. Tripp said she made clear to the ex-White House intern that 
``I did not think this was cool'' to be having a relationship with 
Clinton. Mrs. Tripp said she refrained from criticizing Mrs. Lewis 
to Ms. Lewinsky because of the close mother-daughter relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	Tripp's appearance on ``Larry King Live'' was her second  
broadcast appearance in four days. She gave her first in-depth 
interview on NBC's ``Today Show'' last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
