<DOCNO> APW19990215.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 12:16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Forget Impeachment Saga </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly three of every four Americans say the  
Senate should drop the Monica Lewinsky matter completely and not 
debate a censure resolution against President Clinton, according to 
a new poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-one percent of those surveyed in the Gallup poll,  
conducted for CNN and USA Today and made public Monday, said they 
were pleased by the Senate's decision not to convict Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventy-three percent of those asked said they would rather see  
the Senate ``drop the matter entirely.'' Twenty-six percent said 
they would like to see the Senate debate a resolution to formally 
censure Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll reflected continuing high support for Clinton, giving  
him an approval rating of 68 percent, 10 points higher than when 
the Lewinsky scandal broke 13 months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone survey of 1,034 adults, conducted Friday and  
Saturday, has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate poll, The Los Angeles Times reported that most  
Americans think the Senate was right to acquit Clinton of 
impeachment charges and believe Republicans pursued the matter for 
political reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty-five percent of those surveyed after Friday's Senate vote  
supported the acquittal, while 30 percent thought Clinton should 
have been removed from office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
