<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 12:53:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Joyner's Daughter Gives Inspiration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Only 8 years old, Mary Joyner is filling the  
breach left by the death of her mother, providing mental and 
spiritual inspiration for her father. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I'm still alive is because of my daughter,'' Al  
Joyner, the husband of the late Florence Griffith Joyner, said 
Monday at the New York Track Writers' luncheon. ``I never thought 
I'd say that. Florence laid the foundation for Mary. She's gotten 
her strong personality and beliefs from her mother. Recently, she 
said her mother was very brave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffith Joyner not only was courageous, she was the world's  
fastest woman in 1988, when she won Olympic gold medals in the 100 
and 200 meters and the 400 relay and set world records in the two 
individual events. She died last Sept. 21 at 38 when she was 
stricken with a seizure as she slept and suffocated. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the lives of Al and Mary have been tumultuous and  
filled with grief. Joyner said a day hasn't gone by that thoughts 
of his wife haven't filled his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the hardest thing I've had to deal with in my life,'' he  
said. ``I'm finding out hard hard it is to raise a kid.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On many of those occasions, his precocious daughter has provided  
an uplift. 
</P>
<P>
	Joyner recalled one poignant moment, three weeks after his  
wife's death. 
</P>
<P>
	He and Mary were visiting Universal Studios in Los Angeles, a  
popular family gathering place. Suddenly, Joyner, recalling the 
good times he and Florence had enjoyed before her death, put his 
head down and began crying. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately, his daughter provided the proper soothing words.  
</P>
<P>
	``She said when God calls us home, we'll see mommy again,'' the  
emotional Joyner said. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been many other touching moments.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I put her to sleep, she says I don't want anything to  
happen to you,'' Joyner said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's been a joy. She's able to know what happened to her  
mother. 
</P>
<P>
	``She says things like, `Mommy would have looked good in that  
dress.' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's all right. I see why she's concerned about me, because  
I'm not all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another time last year, when Joyner was addressing his  
daughter's class, he told the pupils he was 26. 
</P>
<P>
	``She embarrassed me,'' he said, jokingly. ``She said I was  
38.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Little Mary, a third-grader who had been a gymnast, now has  
taken up running, just like her mother. However, she not only likes 
sprinting but hurdling, an event in which her father dabbled after 
winning the Olympic gold medal in the triple jump in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's now putting up hurdles in the house and jumping over  
them,'' Joyner said. ``She can clear women's hurdles (33 inches 
high). She's even impressed a lot of people at UCLA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a sprinter, she keeps beating everyone in her school, St.  
John's in Mission Viejo, CaIif., her proud father said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They keep challenging her, and she keeps beating them,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They keep asking her if she is going back to gymnastics. She  
keeps putting up hurdles. She went to UCLA and showed the freshmen 
the drills. It was embarrassing. She uses the balance beam in the 
house as a hurdle. And she had me acting as a hurdle. She told me 
to get down on the floor and she jumped over me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Joyner was in town to promote Florence's book, ``Running for  
Dummies,'' which he finished after his wife died. 
</P>
<P>
	``I share my wife's wishes and dreams,'' he said. ``She put her  
heart and soul into that book. She was an inspiration.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 01:22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks End Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose today for the third  
consecutive trading day, supported by last week's government 
decision to pump public funds into the nation's major banks. The 
dollar slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 81.03 points,  
or 0.58 percent, closing the day's trading at 14,054.72. On Friday, 
the index rose 21.29 points, or 0.15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.08 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
0.24 yen from its level Friday in Tokyo and also below its New York 
level of 114.21 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan announced on Friday a plan to inject $66  
billion in public funds into 15 major banks in an attempt to 
prevent Japan's banking system from collapsing. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also got a boost after the central bank said late Friday  
it was cutting a key interest rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan's policy board lowered its target for  
overnight call money -- the rate banks charge each other for 
unsecured short-term loans -- to an all-time low of 0.15 percent 
from 0.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower interest rates tend to cut borrowing costs for companies,  
helping to spur the nation's economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not as though the banks' bad loan problems will be  
solved with this measure,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager of 
the stock division at Tokyo Securities. ``But at least it relieves 
worries about the banks having a capital shortage come the end of 
the fiscal year in March,'' Hatae said. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 338  
million shares, down from Friday's turnover of 452 million shares. 
Advances outnumbered declines 659 to 448, with 173 issues 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 5.49 points, or 0.50 percent, to 1,095.02. The 
TOPIX rose 6.44 points, or 0.59 percent, Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, trading remained thin ahead of the U.S.  
national holiday today and the Chinese New Year holidays in Hong 
Kong and Singapore on Tuesday and Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the market largely shrugged off other potential  
market-moving factors today, including rising U.S.-Japan trade 
friction over steel and figures showing that Japan's current 
account surplus rose by 13 percent in December from a year earlier, 
pushing the total for all of 1998 to a record high. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 128.70 yen, up from  
128.54 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 2.135 percent from Friday's finish of 2.080 percent, 
driving its price down to 97.39 yen from 97.81 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 05:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Earnhardt, Gordon Dueled to the End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Dale Earnhardt gave Jeff Gordon a  
push just when he needed it most. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy backfired -- and Earnhardt, of all people, should  
have known better at the Daytona 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt chose Gordon as his partner in a late-race move to the  
front that set up a thrilling showdown Sunday in NASCAR's biggest 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	A few laps later, The Intimidator had learned his lesson -- and  
seen his chance for a second straight Daytona 500 victory lost in 
the exhaust of the Kid's steadfast driving and dominating car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was trying all I could do to get to the 24,'' Earnhardt said  
of the final dash for the title. 
</P>
<P>
	``His car was pretty strong off the corners. If I could have  
just got to him in the corner, I might could have got under him, 
but I just couldn't get there. I got beat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, but what a way to go down.  
</P>
<P>
	The drama began with 10 laps remaining, when Gordon slid under  
leader Rusty Wallace heading toward the first turn. He then 
squeezed past Ricky Rudd's lapped car, avoiding a crash by about a 
foot. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt's teammate, Mike Skinner, moved alongside Wallace on  
the outside and they drove three-wide into turn three. 
</P>
<P>
	With Earnhardt bumping Gordon from the back to help him get by,  
Gordon came out in front at the flagstand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was definitely bumping me back there and I wanted him to,''  
Gordon said. ``I was saying, `Come on, hit me harder.' He wasn't 
hitting me hard enough as far as I was concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few laps later, Earnhardt made a move and racing fans got an  
exciting duel seen all too seldom during a pair of great careers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though we battled for a (series) championship in '95, we  
really didn't get to have many tight battles all the way to the 
finish,'' Gordon said. ``I really can't think of a better way to do 
it than here at the Daytona 500.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once it became a two-man race, Gordon set the pace, slowing and  
speeding at the perfect times, keeping just the right amount of air 
between their cars to prevent Earnhardt from using the draft to 
slingshot past him. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt's best hope would have been to get a bump from  
Skinner, but he was in fourth, pinned behind rookie Kenny Irwin. 
Asked if he could have used Skinner's help, Earnhardt snapped. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you take a car out from between us and get (Skinner)  
behind me,'' he said. ``It's not like he can say, `Hey, I'm moving 
up,' and just drive over the other guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the final lap, Earnhardt zigged in, zagged out, zigged in  
again, then made one desperate lunge at Gordon before the finish 
line. 
</P>
<P>
	Each time he tried to get by, Gordon blocked him. Only a  
quarter-mile after the race ended did the seven-time Winston Cup 
winner catch up, giving a victory-lap nudge to congratulate him. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as I'm concerned, especially at Daytona, Dale is so  
good,'' Gordon said. ``He knows the air very, very well. And he 
knows how to make passes without getting help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he had given it to exactly the wrong guy.  
</P>
<P>
	So, there was no celebration for Earnhardt, no using his car to  
carve circles in the grass, the way he did last year when he 
finally took the only major championship to elude him over his 
25-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	And there was no repeat, a la John Elway, the Denver Broncos  
quarterback who won two straight Super Bowls and inspired 
Earnhardt. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it was his fifth second-place finish at Daytona, making  
him the all-time leader in that category, passing Cale Yarbrough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were happy to get second, but we sure would love to be down  
there in Victory Lane,'' Earnhardt said. ``We've had a good week 
here. Everything worked good for us in the qualifying races and we 
had a good day here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also was one of the best finishes in the 41-year history of  
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Earnhardt left thinking of one way it could have been  
even better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 05:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
