<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 12:16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quantrill Not Sure When He'll Pitch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUNEDIN, Fla. (AP) -- Toronto Blue Jays right-hander Paul  
Quantrill, rehabilitating a broken right leg, isn't sure when he'll 
be ready to pitch again. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just going to depend when the muscles are back,'' he said  
Monday at the Blue Jays' spring training complex. ``One day 
something's bothering me, and three days later it's 100 percent 
better. I've already started throwing and doing as much of my 
normal routine as possible, like every year. But I haven't thrown 
off a mound yet. It's coming back real quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quantrill, broke his right leg in a snowmobile accident Jan. 6.  
He was 3-4 with seven saves and a 2.59 ERA in 82 games last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a really good therapist and the Blue Jays have been  
helping me out a lot,'' Quantrill said. ``But chasing my two kids 
around on one or two legs gets you better, pretty quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quantrill is using a cane to get around. The Blue Jays project  
him to return around the end of May. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did the crutch thing long enough,'' he said. ``I don't need  
them now, and the crutch is so that I don't limp. ... When I walk 
the muscle gives out a little bit, and the cane is just there to 
make sure I don't form a habit of limping.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quantrill's contract calls for a $1.4 million salary this year,  
but because snowmobiling falls into ``risky activity'' territory, 
the Blue Jays may be within their rights to void his contract in 
exchange for 30 days' pay, about $235,000. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the snowmobile is idle.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just sitting out there, staring at me and calling my  
name,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 15:56:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Hints at Mexico Ally Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- President Clinton offered a strong hint  
Monday that he will certify Mexico as a reliable ally in the 
difficult struggle against drugs, saying cooperation ``has clearly 
improved'' under President Ernesto Zedillo. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Mexico's disappointing record on extraditions and a drop  
last year in cocaine and heroin seizures, Clinton found positive 
things to say about Mexico's efforts. He welcomed a plan announced 
two weeks ago to invest up to $500 million in a new anti-drug 
initiative and declared, ``The United States is ready to do all we 
can to support you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By law, the president has to judge Mexico's performance on drugs  
by March 1. Mexico would be hit with economic penalties if Clinton 
gave it a failing grade. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Zedillo conferred at a hacienda with manicured  
gardens in the middle of Merida's Mayan archeological zone and then 
addressed 1,400 people in the domed Peon Contreras Theater in 
downtown Merida. Hundreds of people lined the narrow, tree-shaded 
street leading to the theater. 
</P>
<P>
	The president's trip was his first outing since his acquittal  
Friday in the Senate's impeachment trial. Repeating his wish after 
the verdict, Clinton said, ``I think this is a time for 
reconciliation and renewal. I think what we have to do is to serve 
the American people. And if we keep that in mind I think everything 
will be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Attorney General Janet  
Reno, Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater, drug policy 
coordinator Barry McCaffrey and Export-Import Bank chief James 
Harmon signed a series of agreements with their Mexican 
counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	The key initiative was a two-year, $4 billion line of Ex-Im  
credit for Mexican businesses that ``buy American.'' In addition, a 
civil aviation accord will liberalize flights between the United 
States and Mexico, estimated to be worth hundreds of millions of 
dollars to airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Another accord was aimed at promoting border safety and human  
rights, addressing Mexican complaints about the deaths of illegal 
immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton won applause when he noted that Mexico is the largest  
Spanish-speaking country in the world and added, ``Before long, the 
United States will be the second largest Spanish speaking country 
in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said that he and Zedillo ``made progress in areas today  
where, to be charitable, we have not always agreed. Not long ago, 
we could not have had a conversation about drugs without falling 
into an unwinnable argument about who is to blame. That has 
changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people recognize we must reduce our demand for  
drugs,'' the president said. ``The Mexican people recognize that 
ending the drug trade is a national security and public health 
imperative for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, Zedillo called Clinton and his wife, Hillary, ``dearest  
friends,'' and displayed a touch of nationalist pride when he said: 
``For Mexicans, the commitment to fight drugs is first and foremost 
a commitment to ourselves, to our children ... to our safety and to 
our future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican president said his people were ``convinced and  
determined to keep up the fight against drugs until we win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another Mexican priority, Zedillo said, is ``a safe, clean and  
productive border -- a source of pride for the communities that 
share that border.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 15:56:16 </DATE_TIME>
