<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen early Tuesday on  
reports the Japanese government may take steps to curb the recent 
rise in long-term interest rates. Japanese stocks surged higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 115.82 yen in early trading, up 1.74 yen from  
late Monday in Tokyo. U.S. markets were closed Monday for the 
Presidents Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 206.92  
points, or 1.47 percent, to 14,261.64 points in the first 30 
minutes of trading. On Monday, the average closed up 81.03 points, 
or 0.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar's advance came after local news  
reports Tuesday that the government has decided that the Finance 
Ministry's Trust Fund Bureau will temporarily resume its purchases 
of Japanese government bonds to bring interest rates down. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market was rocked recently when the buruea, which  
manages public pension funds and deposits from the country's 
massive postal savings system, announced it would discontinue 
purchases of government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyodo News agency also said the government will reduce the  
amount of long-term government bonds to be issued next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.940 percent from Monday's finish of 2.140 percent, 
driving its price up to 98.89 yen from 98.35 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.66 yen, up  
128.70 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower interest rates tend to reduce borrowing costs for  
companies, and could help spur economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, export-oriented auto issues such as Toyota  
Motor and Honda Motor led the way as investors were cheered up by 
the yen's retreat against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker yen tends to make Japanese exports cheaper aboard and  
thus more competitive, helping to boost earnings of export-led 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section added 9.20 points, or 0.84 percent, to 
1,104.22. The TOPIX closed up 5.49 points, or 0.50 percent, the day 
before. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
