<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	American Airlines Gets Set to Fly  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines expects to operate almost  
normally tomorrow following 10 days during which more than 6,000 
flights were canceled due to a pilot sickout. About 250 of the 
2,250 flights scheduled today were canceled. But AMR Corp., 
American's parent company, and the pilots resumed talks over the 
integration of the recently purchased Reno Air. At its worst, 
nearly 2,500 of American's 9,400 pilots went on the sick list last 
week, forcing the airline to cancel more than half of its 2,250 
scheduled flights each day. 

</P>
<P>
	Tripp Says Lewinsky Was Suicidal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Linda Tripp said tonight that Monica Lewinsky  
became suicidal out of fear that President Clinton would learn that 
the former White House intern had confided their relationship to 
friends. Appearing on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Tripp said that 
Lewinsky was ``not suicidal'' due to Clinton ``dumping her'' but 
because of her ``biggest fear that he would find out she shared her 
story with somebody else.'' She revealed that she is ``seriously 
considering'' writing a book about her experiences, a project she 
said she abandoned in 1996 because she was afraid of losing her 
job. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks New Start  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- On the first outing since his acquittal in  
the Senate impeachment trial, President Clinton called today for a 
fresh political start. ``I think this is a time for reconciliation 
and renewal,'' he told reporters during summit talks in Mexico. ``I 
think what we have to do is to serve the American people. And if we 
keep that in mind I think everything will be fine. We can't solve 
the challenges of Social Security and Medicare and education and 
these other things, we can't keep the international economy going 
unless we have a level of cooperation.'' 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-Mexico Summit Held  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- President Clinton today hinted that he  
will officially certify Mexico as a reliable U.S. ally in the war 
on drugs. At summit talks, he said cooperation ``has clearly 
improved'' under President Ernesto Zedillo. Mexico's record on 
extraditions and on cocaine and heroin seizures had been seen as a 
problem. However, Clinton welcomed a plan to invest up to $500 
million in a new anti-drug initiative. ``The United States is ready 
to do all we can to support you,'' Clinton vowed. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Warns Iraq on Threat  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright  
warned today the U.S. ``response would be swift and sure'' if Iraq 
attacked the Turkish base American planes are using to patrol its 
skies. Iraqi vice president Taha Yassin Ramadan threatened that 
Iraq will attack the Incirlik base if American jets keep 
patrolling. Today U.S. warplanes fired on defense sites in northern 
Iraq, the Defense Department said in Washington. The Pentagon said 
the planes returned safely to Incirlik. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Nixon Aide Ehrlichman Dies  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- John D. Ehrlichman, 73, who was President Nixon's  
domestic affairs adviser, is dead. Ehrlichman died yesterday of 
natural causes at his home in Atlanta. He had suffered from 
diabetes, his son said. Ehrlichman went to prison in 1976 and 
served 18 months for obstruction of justice, conspiracy and 
perjury. He quit politics, moved to Santa Fe, N.M., wrote political 
novels and became a radio commentator. 

</P>
<P>
	Seat-Belt Use Rises  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After being stalled for years, the percentage  
of Americans wearing seat belts increased in 1998. The national 
percentage jumped from 62.2 percent to 65.1 percent around Memorial 
Day, and from 69.6 percent to 70.1 percent around Thanksgiving, 
said the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration in figures 
the agency was releasing tomorrow. Police organizations have 
started widespread campaigns to enforce seat belt laws. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Mark the New Year  
</P>
<P>
	MACAU (AP) -- China and communities of Chinese across Asia on  
Tuesday welcomed the Year of the Rabbit. It marks the 4,697th year 
of the traditional Chinese calendar. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks surged higher on Tuesday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average rose 206.92 points to 14,261.64 in early 
trading. U.S. markets were closed on Monday for Presidents Day. 

</P>
<P>
	Vikings Deal QB Johnson to 'Skins  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Quarterback Brad Johnson of the Minnesota  
Vikings was traded today to the Washington Redskins. The Redskins 
will give up first- and third-round draft choices this year and a 
second-round pick in 2000. Washington obtained Johnson after its 
starting quarterback, Trent Green, signed with St. Louis as a free 
agent. 

</P>
<P>
	No.10 St. John's Slams Providence  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lavor Postell scored 17 points to lead No. 10  
St. John's to a 104-70 victory over Providence tonight. The Red 
Storm is 21-6; 12-3 in the Big East. Providence is 14-11; 7-8 in 
the Big East. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

</P>
</TEXT>
