<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Orleans Revels in Mardi Gras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- On the eve of Mardi Gras, the Crescent City  
was nearly in full party mode. 
</P>
<P>
	By Monday, tens of thousands of revelers were already gathered,  
drinking and dancing, bourbon in hand and beads around their necks. 
Parades filled the streets, music filled the air and New Orleans 
resident A.J. Hingle couldn't have been happier. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just getting juiced up for Mardi Gras,'' Hingle said as he  
picked up a 12-ounce beer from a stand near the stage at a 
riverfront park where a band was about to rock. 
</P>
<P>
	George and Brenda Holyfield of Los Angeles were waiting for the  
band, and for a Carnival first -- a formal meeting between the 
make-believe monarchs of the city's most prestigious black and 
white Carnival parade groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex, King of Carnival, and King Zulu of the Zulu Social Aid and  
Pleasure Club were meeting as part of a giant open-air music and 
fireworks show heralding Lundi Gras, or Fat Monday, a warm-up for 
the raucous citywide Fat Tuesday street party that precedes Lent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Zulu! It's going to be a big party,'' said Holyfield. ``That's  
what we're looking forward to. It's going to be the wildest thing 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Holyfields and Hingle were among several hundred people on  
the riverfront enjoying drinks and food bought from the bank of 
stands, the sun, and the hooting tunes of a nearby riverboat's 
calliope concert. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zulu parade, which opens Mardi Gras, was the biggest draw  
for Holyfield, and Mrs. Holyfield said she was enjoying the food 
more than anything else on the trip. ``Crawfish etouffe, oysters 
and all the fried foods. And the seafood gumbo. Everything's just 
great. I'm enjoying it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hingle said he was just waiting for the band, Bag of Donuts.  
It's one of his favorites on the New Orleans bar circuit, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lead singer wore a cheerleader's skirt, a purple shirt with  
football shoulder pads and a jester hat in the Mardi Gras colors of 
purple, green and gold. One guitarist was shirtless, with 
black-streaked whiteface makeup a la Kiss; the other wore a pink 
dress and a construction hard hat. 
</P>
<P>
	They weren't Carnival outfits, though -- that's what they always  
wear, Hingle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Phelan's shirt front was hidden under string upon string of  
beads, most of them the long shiny sort paradegoers screamed and 
pleaded for -- and sometimes bared flesh to win from those passing 
by on floats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen people go as crazy as they do over beads,''  
said Phelan, of Marlboro, N.Y. He was finishing a two-week stay in 
New Orleans on a trip he'd promised himself for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I passed through here 42 years ago, a week after the Mardi  
Gras. And I always said I'm coming back for the Mardi Gras. I'm 
here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
