<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Avalanche Leaves 1 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLINGHAM, Wash. (AP) -- One snowboarder is dead, a second is  
missing and two others narrowly escaped injury after being caught 
in a massive avalanche on Mount Baker. 
</P>
<P>
	The body of Justin M. Parker, 19, was found Sunday beneath about  
10 feet of snow. A search for Sean Riches, 25, was suspended until 
the avalanche danger subsides. 
</P>
<P>
	``The avalanche ... is just a small amount of what's ready to  
fall,'' said Ron Peterson, Whatcom County's search and rescue 
supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	The slide came down about 12:30 p.m. Sunday and covered an area  
about a mile long, 100 feet wide and 12 feet deep in Rumble Gully, 
just outside the Mount Baker Ski Area, about 90 miles northeast of 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Freymeyer, operators leader for Bellingham Mountain Rescue,  
said the avalanche was the largest he had seen on the 10,778-foot 
peak. 
</P>
<P>
	Two skiers or snowboarders whose names were not available  
managed to free themselves after being caught in the slide, 
Peterson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still missing in Rumble Gully is Jason Edward Carey Fuller, 25,  
a snowboarder who vanished in an avalanche in mid-January. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, five people were killed in avalanches in  
California, Colorado and Utah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
