<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Misanthrope' Misses the Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Posturing and preening are the watch words of  
the Classic Stage Company's relentless revival of ``The 
Misanthrope,'' currently running off-Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	This acrid adaptation by English playwright Martin Crimp teems  
with trendiness yet drains all the life and the laughs out of one 
of Moliere's most glorious comedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Transposed from 17th century France to present-day London, the  
production has earned an inordinate amount of attention because of 
film actress Uma Thurman, who here plays an American movie star 
named Jennifer. 
</P>
<P>
	The lovely, blond Thurman of ``Pulp Fiction'' fame holds her own  
with such accomplished classically trained actors as Roger Rees and 
Mary Lou Rosato. But Thurman and the rest of the company are faced 
with the law of diminishing returns as they deal with Crimp's 
stilted, sour script. 
</P>
<P>
	Rees is Alceste, the title character, an embittered playwright  
who hungers for the young movie star while trashing his colleagues 
and just about everyone else who gets in his sightlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Rees, Broadway's original Nicholas Nickleby, rants and raves  
with astonishing virtuosity. Not many actors can make combativeness 
attractive, but Rees does, although his highwire bickering has 
nowhere to go. 
</P>
<P>
	Alceste is cautioned in his excesses by good friend John, played  
by the fine Michael Emerson, best known for portraying Oscar Wilde 
in ``Gross Indecency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dialogue is sprinkled with an occasional four-letter word  
and references to such contemporary folk as playwrights David Hare 
and Alan Ayckbourn, composer Andrew Lloyd Webber and media empress 
Tina Brown. The name-droppings sound too clever by half. 
</P>
<P>
	At least designer Narelle Sissons' oddly angled set is fun. It  
suggests a hotel room gone wildly out of control with a mirrored 
backdrop that has the audience appearing as part of the production 
-- and listening conspiratorially to all the gossipy goings-on. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Barry Edelstein has staged this ruckus with precision.  
Clarity is a virtue that can't be overestimated, but in the end, 
this ``Misanthrope'' is as unfunny as it is unpleasant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
