<HEADLINE> Kessem Power Wins San Luis Obispo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Kessem Power, ridden by substitute jockey  
Gary Stevens, overtook 8-5 favorite Brave Act in the late going to 
win Monday's $200,000 San Luis Obispo Handicap at Santa Anita by 
three-quarters of a length. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens got the mount on Kessem Power, a 7-year-old New  
Zealand-bred son of Kessem, after Eddie Delahoussaye phoned in 
sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Kessem Power, who carried 115 pounds, covered 1 1/2 miles on turf  
in 2:28 and, as the fourth-favorite in a field of seven, paid 
$12.40, $4.80 and $2.80. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just push-button, and he's a smart horse who just flies  
home the last quarter,'' Stevens said of Kessem Power, who won for 
the 11th time in 35 starts and earned $120,000 to raise his career 
earnings to $543,624. 
</P>
<P>
	Brave Act, ridden by Goncalino Almeida and carrying high weight  
of 121 pounds, crossed the finish line 1 3/4 lengths in front of Lazy 
Lode and returned $3.20 and $2.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Brave Act won his previous four stakes races including the San  
Gabriel and San Marcos handicaps at the current Santa Anita 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazy Lode, the 2-1 second-favorite ridden by Corey Nakatani and  
carrying 120 pounds, was 4 1/2 lengths ahead of River Bay at the wire 
and paid $2.60 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Following River Bay across the finish line in the 43rd running  
of the race for 4-year-olds and up were Southerly Wind, Native 
Desert and Pompeyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
