Republic's president on Monday urged his country's politicians to 
settle their differences and approve loans to help repair damage 
from Hurricane Georges. 
</P>
<P>
	President Leonel Fernandez invited the leaders of feuding  
parties to a meeting to work out a truce. 
</P>
<P>
	About $300 million in hurricane loans from the World Bank and  
the Interamerican Development Bank, as well as regional economic 
agreements, are on hold because of the political gridlock. 
Fernandez negotiated the loans, but the National Congress needs to 
approve them before they can be granted. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Georges swept over the Dominican Republic on Sept. 22,  
killing at least 283 people and causing more than $2 billion in 
damage. 
</P>
<P>
	For months, Fernandez's Dominican Liberation Party and the  
Social Christian Reformist Party have been locked in a battle 
against the majority Dominican Revolutionary Party over control of 
the Congress. 
</P>
