<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beer Co. Says NLRB Dropping Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch said Monday it has learned that  
the National Labor Relations Board intends to dismiss charges filed 
against the brewer by the Teamsters union. 
</P>
<P>
	The union had challenged the company's implementation last  
September of its final contract offer covering some 8,000 
Anheuser-Busch U.S. brewery employees represented by the union. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased that the Board has recognized we have acted  
properly throughout this process and that it is clear that the 
parties reached impasse,'' said William L. Rammes, the vice 
president of corporate human resources. ``This demonstrates that 
the union's charges to the contrary were without merit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Board officials told the company that it will also dismiss  
another Teamster charge that had challenged the company's 
elimination of union dues checkoff, its protection of internal 
company documents on the implementation process and the format of 
final offer clarifications, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Formal written notification of the Board's decision is expected  
to be received within a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	NLRB offices were closed Monday for the Presidents Day holiday.  
No one at the Teamsters could immediately be reached by the 
Associated Press. 

</P>
</TEXT>
