<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Faldo May Face Woods in 1st Round  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Nick Faldo barely held onto the 65th position in the Official  
World Golf Ranking released today, setting up a possible 
first-round match against No. 1 Tiger Woods in the Andersen 
Consulting Match Play Championship next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's rankings will be used to set the field for the 64-man  
event that begins Feb. 24 at La Costa Resort in Carlsbad, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo, the three-time Masters and British Open champion, would  
play Woods in the first round because Jumbo Ozaki, ranked No. 14, 
has told the PGA Tour that he does not plan to play. 
</P>
<P>
	Ozaki has until Wednesday to change his mind, which is unlikely  
since he rarely leaves Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods solidified his position atop the rankings by winning the  
Buick Invitational Sunday, while No. 2 David Duval was skiing in 
Idaho. Duval would play Stephen Leaney of Australia in the first 
round of the $5 million tournament, the first of the three World 
Golf Championship events. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark O'Meara and Davis Love III are tied at No. 3 in the  
rankings. O'Meara would get the third seed because he has more 
points in the current year and would play Michael Bradley. Love 
would get Steve Pate, with a possible third-round showdown against 
good friend Fred Couples should both advance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be interesting and exciting,'' Love said. ``Guys  
who are buddies playing in practice rounds all of a sudden could 
get matched up. I may end up playing Freddie when I'm usually his 
partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But no match is as tantalizing as Woods and Faldo.  
</P>
<P>
	Faldo, the three-time Masters and British Open champion, hasn't  
won since the Nissan Open at Los Angeles two years ago and has 
missed the cut in his two European tour events this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he is dangerous in match play, having won more Ryder Cup  
matches than anyone in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Between two good professionals on their day, it's anybody's  
game over 18 holes,'' Faldo has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods figures to be the favorite at La Costa, especially after  
going 22-under-par over the weekend in San Diego to win his 10th 
tournament since turning pro in August 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	He is the only player to win three consecutive U.S. Amateur  
titles and recently won the PGA Grand Slam of Golf, match play 
between the major championship winners of 1998 (Woods was the first 
alternate since O'Meara won two majors last year). 
</P>
<P>
	But the dream pairing almost didn't come off. Faldo was on the  
fence at No. 65 when he missed the cut in the Dubai Desert Classic, 
and four players had a good chance to move past him on the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Turner could have tied for third with one other player in  
the Australian Masters to move up to No. 65. He was tied for the 
lead at one point Sunday, but wound up in a three-way tie for third 
and came up two points short. 
</P>
<P>
	David Toms could have moved up to No. 65 with a three-way tie  
for seventh in the Buick Invitational. Toms had a 12-foot birdie 
putt at the 18th hole that would have given him seventh place 
alone, but he missed and finished in a five-way tie for seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Perry had to finish second in the Buick. He closed with a  
66 but finished fourth, five strokes behind runner-up Billy Ray 
Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Per-Ulrik Johansson had to finish in the top 10 in the Dubai  
Desert Classic, but came up four strokes short and was well back. 
</P>
<P>
	The final field will be set at 8 p.m. EST next Monday. Tour  
officials say everyone has committed to play except Ozaki. 
</P>
<P>
	For Faldo, the Match Play is more than a chance to play Woods.  
Last place alone is worth $25,000, which would help him accumulate 
valuable Ryder Cup points. Points for the European team are based 
on official money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
