<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Increase Seen in Seat Belt Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After being stalled for years, the percentage  
of Americans wearing seat belts increased in 1998 -- the same year 
police organizations started widespread campaigns to enforce seat 
belt laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The national percentage jumped from 62.2 percent to 65.1 percent  
around the Memorial Day holiday, and again from 69.6 percent to 
70.1 percent around the Thanksgiving holiday, said the National 
Highway Traffic Safety Administration in figures the agency was 
releasing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Those jumps coincided with weeklong crackdowns in which 4,000  
law enforcement agencies erected checkpoints and ticketed drivers 
who were not wearing seat belts. They also broke a three-year trend 
in which national seat belt usage hovered in the 60 percent range. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials and seat belt advocates plan to use the  
evidence to encourage more states to pass primary seat belt laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Under such laws, which have already been adopted in 14 states  
and the District of Columbia, police can pull over drivers for not 
wearing their seat belt. Under more widespread secondary laws, 
police can ticket drivers for not wearing a seat belt only if they 
have been pulled over for another reason. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say primary laws are needed for two reasons: Seat  
belt use doesn't increase otherwise, and research shows that 
parents who do not wear seat belts themselves are more likely to 
leave their children unbuckled. Car accidents are the No. 1 killer 
of children 14 and under. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we know what's killing our kids and we're not applying the  
medicine, shame on us as a nation for not acting,'' said Janet 
Dewey, executive director of the Air Bag &AMP; Seat Belt Safety 
Campaign. The group, sponsored by the auto industry and insurance 
companies, works in conjunction with the Transportation Department 
and the highway safety administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign announced Monday it was sending children to 11  
Statehouses across the country to lobby governors and legislative 
leaders for primary laws. It also planned lobbying campaigns in 
Florida, Ohio, Alabama, Illinois, Virginia and New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Dr. Ricardo Martinez,  
head of the safety administration, were holding a separate news 
conference in Washington on Tuesday to unveil the government 
statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, the numbers showed that 19 million more Americans wore  
seat belts in 1998. If they continue to do so this year, the 
government estimates some 1,500 lives will be saved. 
</P>
<P>
	Seat belt statistics have traditionally been unreliable. Some  
states measure usage by all drivers, while others check only car 
drivers and not those in trucks or sports-utility vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration  
had an independent firm scientifically measure seat belt usage 
around the crackdowns. Two sets of surveys were conducted, one 
before and after Memorial Day and the other around the Thanksgiving 
holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	They showed a cumulative increase from 62.2 percent before  
Memorial Day to 70.1 percent after Thanksgiving. 
</P>
<P>
	In surveys completed by the same firm in 1994 and 1996, the  
safety administration found seat belt usage to be 58.9 percent and 
61 percent, respectively. Publicly released figures -- based on the 
more unreliable state statistics -- set the figure at 68 percent for 
the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a $203 billion highway bill passed last year by Congress,  
states must begin compiling statistics in much the same manner used 
internally by the safety administration. That should lead to more 
reliable reporting in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, both the government and seat belt groups believe  
that previous seat belt campaigns have reached all of the Americans 
who are going to buckle up willingly. Now they think new laws, 
stricter enforcement and harsh advertising campaigns are needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the National Highway Traffic Safety  
Administration replaced TV ads featuring the lovable crash test 
dummies Vince and Larry with more gruesome spots showing unbuckled 
drivers hurt in crashes around their neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	After each accident, a caption on the screen asks, ``Didn't see  
that coming? No one ever does. Buckle up.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
