<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Jaki Byard    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jaki Byard, a pianist, saxophonist and music  
teacher who recorded with modern jazz artists Charles Mingus and 
Rahasaan Roland Kirk, was found shot dead at his home on Thursday. 
He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were investigating the shooting, which went unheard by  
Byard's family members. 
</P>
<P>
	Byard's playing spanned the history of jazz. His improvisations  
included boogie-woogie and free jazz with zippy stylistic changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Byard taught for several decades and was instrumental in the  
re-evaluation of jazz history that began in the late 1970s. Early 
in his career he was a big player in the Boston jazz scene. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1960s, Byard began recording with Mingus. He played  
on the classic albums ``Mingus Mingus Mingus Mingus Mingus'' and 
``The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Duke Ellington became sick just before he died, Byard  
played piano in the Ellington Orchestra. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Denise B. Cavins    	
</P>
<P>
	JACKSON, Mich. (AP) -- Denise B. Cavins, a reporter for The  
Jackson Citizen Patriot for 32 years, died Sunday of cancer. She 
was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	During her career she covered a wide range of stories including  
Jackson Republicans at the 1981 inauguration of President Reagan 
and a series of articles on Nickolas B. Peck, a hockey player who 
lost his lower legs to meningitis in December 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	She worked for two years at the South Bend Tribune in Indiana  
before starting at the Citizen Patriot in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last seven years of her career, Ms. Cavins covered  
government and school news in Blackman Township, the western side 
of Jackson County and eastern part of Calhoun County. She retired 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include her mother, brother-in-law, two nieces, a  
nephew and two great-nephews. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Harry A. Cole    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Retired Judge Harry A. Cole, the first black to  
serve on the state's highest court and to be elected to the state 
Senate, died Sunday of complications from pneumonia. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole became the first black to win a state Senate seat in 1954.  
In 1977, he was the first black named to the Maryland Court of 
Appeals, where he served until his retirement in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	During his tenure on the court, Cole wrote the unanimous opinion  
that upheld the right of the state to fund abortions for poor 
women. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Jimmy Dudley    	
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Jimmy Dudley, the radio voice of the  
Cleveland Indians from 1948, the year the team won its last World 
Series, until 1967, died Friday of a stroke. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	After apprenticing as an announcer for the Chicago Cubs after  
the war, he was hired by the Indians. He also did play-by-play for 
the Cleveland Browns in the 1950s, for the Baltimore Colts and for 
Ohio State University football games. 
</P>
<P>
	He became the voice of the Seattle Pilots in 1969, but a year  
later, the team transferred to Milwaukee, leaving him behind. 
Dudley never announced a major league game again. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley was inducted into the broadcasters' wing of the Baseball  
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
                         *John D. Ehrlichman    	
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- John D. Ehrlichman, President Nixon's domestic  
affairs adviser who was imprisoned for 18 months for the Watergate 
conspiracy, died Sunday of natural causes. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Ehrlichman, who along with H.R. Haldeman was one of Nixon's two  
top advisers, resigned from his White House post in April 1973 and 
was convicted two years later for obstruction of justice, 
conspiracy and perjury in the attempted cover-up of the burglary of 
the Democratic National Committee offices at the Watergate complex 
in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	As the cover-up began to unravel and pressure mounted, Nixon  
summoned Haldeman and domestic counsel John Ehrlichman to the 
presidential cabin at Camp David, Md., in April 1973 and told them 
they would have to resign. The next day, he fired White House 
counsel John Dean, and accepted the resignations of Haldeman, 
Ehrlichman and Attorney General Richard Kleindienst. 
</P>
<P>
	Under threat of impeachment, Nixon resigned on Aug. 9, 1974. He  
was later pardoned by President Ford. 
</P>
<P>
	Ehrlichman spent 18 months at Swift Trail Camp, a  
minimum-security federal prison south of Safford, Ariz., and was 
released in 1978. Haldeman also served 18 months in prison and died 
in November 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	After getting out of prison, he moved to Santa Fe, N.M., where  
he began a new career as an artist, writer and commentator. 
Ehrlichman wrote four novels: ``The Company'' 1976; ``The Whole 
Truth'' 1979; ``The China Card'' 1986; (co-author) of ``The Rigby 
File'' 1989. He also wrote a memoir that was published in 1983, 
``Witness to Power: The Nixon Years.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Libero Gualtieri    	
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Sen. Libero Gualtieri, who led the parliamentary  
inquiry into the kidnap-murder of Italian Prime Minister Aldo Moro, 
died Monday of an aneurism. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	While president of the Parliamentary Commission on Massacres  
from 1988 to 1994, Gualtieri investigated the 1978 murder of Moro, 
who was kidnapped and then slain by members of the Red Brigades. 
</P>
<P>
	Gualtieri also led the parliamentary probe into the 1980 crash  
of a domestic airliner near the island of Ustica. Investigators 
never learned what caused the DC-9 to blow apart, killing 81 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Gualtieri also investigated alleged illicit activities by the  
Italian secret services. 
</P>
<P>
	Gualtieri joined the Democrats of the Left in the last  
legislature. First elected in 1979, he had held his previous seats 
with the Republican Party. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Buddy Wayne Knox    	
</P>
<P>
	BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) -- Buddy Wayne Knox, a rockabilly singer  
and songwriter who hit the top of the charts with ``Party Doll'' ih 
the 1950s, died Sunday of cancer. He was 65. 
</P>
<P>
	Knox penned his biggest hit, ``Party Doll,'' as early as 1948.  
Seven years later, he formed the Rhythm Orchids with Jimmy Bowen on 
bass and Don Lanier on guitar. Studio owner Norman Petty cut 
``Party Doll'' and Bowen's ``I'm Stickin' With You'' on the local 
Triple-D label in 1956, using a cardboard box instead of drums. 
</P>
<P>
	The tunes were later picked up by Roulette's then-new NYC label,  
which split the songs onto two records, each with a ``B'' side. 
</P>
<P>
	Each sold a million copies and ``Party Doll'' became a No. 1  
hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Knox had a string of other songs on the charts in the '50s,  
including ``Hula Love,'' ``Rock Your Little Baby To Sleep,'' and 
``Somebody Touched Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Knox joined The Crickets, Bobby Vee and The Shirelles  
at a Buddy Holly Tribute concert to mark the 38th anniversary of 
the singer's death. Concerts commemorating ``the day that music 
died'' -- as singer-songwriter Don McLean put it in his 1972 hit 
``American Pie'' -- have become an annual event. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Max Samter    	
</P>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Dr. Max Samter, a leader in the treatment  
of people with allergies who was known for his groundbreaking 
textbook on immunology, died Feb. 9. He was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter was the first to recognize that patients who had both  
asthma and nasal polyps, a severe inflammation of the tissue lining 
the nose or sinuses, could have a dangerous reaction to aspirin. 
Such patients are now said to have Samter's syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter was president of the American Academy of Allergy, Asthma  
and Immunology in 1958-59 and helped establish the International 
Association of Allergology in the 1950s. He retired from the 
University of Illinois in 1975 but continued to treat patients 
until 1992. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Doug Weston    	
</P>
<P>
	WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Doug Weston, founder of the  
nightclub Troubadour that showcased such folk, rock and comedy acts 
as Joan Baez, Elton John and Lenny Bruce, died Sunday. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston prided himself in the acts and audiences he attracted for  
more than four decades, from singer Linda Ronstadt to comedians 
such as the Smothers Brothers and Cheech &AMP; Chong. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston first set up shop in the 1950s in a 65-seat coffeehouse  
on La Cienega Boulevard. By 1957 he had made enough money to open 
the 300-seat Troubadour in West Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the club's acts were consistently impressive:  
the Byrds, Judy Collins, Bill Cosby, the Committee, Bo Diddley, 
Arlo Guthrie, Richie Havens, Gordon Lightfoot, Roger Miller, Joni 
Mitchell, Laura Nyro, Mort Sahl, Kris Kristofferson and Nina 
Simone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
