<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 05:45:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Impeachment Spread Fame Around </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The yearlong Monica Lewinsky saga thrust the  
proverbial 15 minutes of fame upon a cast of ordinary people. Some 
relished the limelight, while others grudgingly lost the comforts 
of their anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	White House steward Bayani Nelvis and Oval Office secretary  
Betty Currie looked uneasy when hordes of photographers and 
cameramen surrounded them as they walked into the federal 
courthouse to testify before Kenneth Starr's grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Several White House aides ran up huge legal bills. Catherine  
Allday Davis, a high school friend of Ms. Lewinsky, had to fly all 
the way from Japan to testify. Larry Cockell, the tall, stern 
Secret Service agent who stands beside the president in public, was 
temporarily removed as his chief bodyguard during the legal battle 
over his grand jury testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	And Andrew Bleiler, a Portland, Ore., theater technician, lost  
his marriage over his admission of a five-year affair with Ms. 
Lewinsky. He separated from his wife and plans to divorce. 
</P>
<P>
	But for every figure who counted a personal loss in the  
presidential scandal, another seemed to flourish. 
</P>
<P>
	Book agent Lucianne Goldberg, who encouraged Linda Tripp to make  
the secret tapes that divulged Ms. Lewinsky's affair with President 
Clinton, savored her fame. ``We wanted to be at the center of it,'' 
she told a magazine interviewer. 
</P>
<P>
	A frequent television guest, Goldberg will try to keep her  
profile high with a new radio talk show. But her son, Jonah, who 
used to get 25 to 30 interview requests a week, now gets few. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went through my five minutes of withdrawal after my 15  
minutes of fame was up,'' said Jonah Goldberg, a writer and 
television producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet gossip columnist Matt Drudge, first to report  
allegations of the Lewinsky-Clinton affair, parlayed his sudden 
fame into his own 30-minute weekly TV show on the Fox network. 
</P>
<P>
	William Ginsburg, the garrulous California malpractice attorney  
who first represented Ms. Lewinsky, became a ubiquitous presence on 
TV talk shows -- once appearing on five in a single day. But the 
spotlight quickly faded after he was replaced last April by two 
Washington-savvy lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	And Abe Hirschfeld, an eccentric New York real estate magnate,  
invited the cameras to him. At a news conference he offered Paula 
Jones $1 million to settle her sexual harassment lawsuit against 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	But most will now recede into distant memories of a tawdry  
presidential scandal that most Americans could not wait to end. As 
artist Andy Warhol predicted, anyone can be famous, but not for 
very long. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all going to fade, and no one will remember who these  
people were,'' said Thomas Sokolowski, director of The Andy Warhol 
Museum in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 07:14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich To Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House  
Budget Committee and a champion of tax cuts, laid the groundwork 
today for a longshot presidential campaign based on returning 
``power to the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to begin to run America from the bottom up,'' Kasich  
told a crowd of 1,300 cheering supporters in his adopted hometown. 
They attended a $100-a-person breakfast this morning that followed 
a $1,000-a-person dinner Sunday night that attracted 300 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, a nine-term Republican congressman who has been pushing  
for a 10 percent, across-the-board tax cut, announced his plans to 
file papers with the Federal Election Commission to formally 
establish a presidential exploratory committee. Supporters planned 
a rally at Port Columbus International Airport before Kasich left 
for Iowa and New Hampshire, the states that set the primary 
front-runners. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, 46, joins Sen. John McCain of Arizona, conservative  
activist Gary Bauer, former Vice President Dan Quayle and former 
Secretary of Education Lamar Alexander as Republicans with 
exploratory committees. 
</P>
<P>
	An Ohio State University Buckeyes fight song played as Kasich  
entered a hotel ballroom to address supporters today. The crowd 
waved red signs saying ``Run, John, Run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hungry for the renewal of the American spirit,'' Kasich  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, it's power from the people and power to the  
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While less well-known than such front-runners as Quaye, Texas  
Gov. George W. Bush or former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole, 
Kasich said voters' lack of familiarity with him could work to his 
advantage. He said he was different from other candidates because 
he was not capitalizing on famous relatives or personal wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just a little different and a little fresher than a lot of  
the people who are in politics now,'' Kasich said Sunday on NBC's 
``Meet the Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a mailman's son from a blue-collar community near  
Pittsburgh,'' Kasich said. ``I got into politics because I wanted 
to change the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich readily admits that he probably won't be able to match  
other candidates' fund-raising skills, but has said he should be 
able to run a credible campaign. He plans to build recognition and 
find donors with the help of the Internet, cable television and 
some offbeat antics, such as a bowling alley tour of Iowa later 
this spring. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 18:22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Praises Clinton for Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton would make a  
``terrific'' senator from New York state, her husband said Monday, 
``but that's a decision that she'll have to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that, President Clinton became the latest member of his  
administration to pump air into a Hillary Clinton-for-Senate 
boomlet. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, whose retirement next  
year will create the vacancy, said New York could use some of Mrs. 
Clinton's ``magnificent, young, bright, able, Illinois-Arkansas 
enthusiasm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She'd be welcome and she'd win,'' Moynihan said.  
</P>
<P>
	Still to be heard from: the potential candidate. About all Mrs.  
Clinton has said about running for the Senate in 2000 is that she 
hasn't had time to think about it -- and she said that through a 
spokesperson. 
</P>
<P>
	What did Mrs. Clinton have to say about her husband's early  
endorsement? ``Nothing,'' said her spokeswoman, Marsha Berry. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, talking to reporters who accompanied him for a meeting  
with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, said the same thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she would be terrific in the Senate. But that's a  
decision that she'll have to make,'' Clinton said. ``And for 
reasons I'm sure you'll understand she hasn't had anything like 
adequate time to talk to the people who think she should do this -- 
much less people who think perhaps she shouldn't. She just hasn't 
had time to deal with this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he wanted everyone to understand that the idea did  
not originate with Mrs. Clinton. ``I don't think it had ever 
occurred to her before a lot of people started calling and asking 
her to do it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then he added, in what amounted to an endorsement:  
</P>
<P>
	``It's her decision to make. I will support whatever decision  
she makes enthusiastically. She has a lot of other opportunities 
for public service that will be out there. She and I both would 
like to continue to be useful in public affairs when we leave 
office. But it's a decision she'll have to make. She'd be great if 
she did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks ago, New York Democratic Chairwoman Judith Hope said  
the odds were 50-50 that Mrs. Clinton would run. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to visit New York City in early March  
for a women's leadership forum and some Democrats think she might 
use that setting to give an indication of her intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City Mayor Rudy Giuliani is a possible Republican  
candidate for the Moynihan seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be an incredible race,'' if both the first lady and  
the mayor ran, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Residency requirements vary among states. In New York a  
candidate need only have purchased or rented a residence by 
Election Day to meet residency requirements for purpose of running 
for office, according to Lee Daghlian, spokesman for the state 
Board of Elections. Robert Kennedy was a latecomer to New York when 
he won a Senate seat in 1964. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
