<DOCNO> APW19990215.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:26:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How Impeachment Change Conversation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Around the horseshoe table of Anna Harvey's  
political science class, when talk turns to impeachment, 16 New 
York University students struggle to understand the oddest 
political year of their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll look back and see this as a time when the American  
public rejected a myth about the president -- that he was supposed 
to be a hero,'' says Jenny Schwehr, a sophomore from California. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you see is a bleeding of two realms of society into each  
other. There's a socializing of politics and a politicization of 
social life,'' says Lenneal Gardner, a junior from New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	And this, from sophomore Katherine Katsoulakis of New York City:  
``People are going to look back and say, `What happened here?''' 
</P>
<P>
	What indeed? The young adults aren't alone in their confusion.  
As they grapple, so does the nation: People are discussing what 
many have never discussed before. For a year, Americans have 
wrestled, out in the open, over what should be seen, what should be 
discussed, what should be part of the public discourse and what 
should stay private. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, a year after C-SPAN collided with ``As the World Turns,''  
have the events in Washington -- sex, lies, videotape and the public 
airing of it all -- made a lasting mark on the national 
conversation? Will Americans ever view politics, prurience and 
public discourse the same way? 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about a national dialogue that has been going on  
for the past year. It has a profound effect upon our sociology, our 
psychology, our relationships,'' says Michael Harrison, editor of 
Talkers, a trade magazine for the talk-show industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``This may be changing, irrevocably, the way we talk to one  
another,'' says Roderick P. Hart, a University of Texas-Austin 
professor who studies communication and government. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential sexual scandal has a venerable tradition, from  
Thomas Jefferson and Grover Cleveland through Warren G. Harding and 
Franklin D. Roosevelt to John F. Kennedy. But two things were 
different in President Clinton's case: The public found out much 
more immediately, and the one-two punch of media and Congress made 
sure the whole matter got in the nation's face -- and stayed there. 
</P>
<P>
	This injected into the national dialogue a variety of unfamiliar  
situations. Explicit sexual material began permeating the nightly 
news. Off-color presidential jokes pushed their way into the 
mainstream. The publisher of Hustler magazine became a political 
player. 
</P>
<P>
	One man recounted the awkwardness of oral-sex discussions with  
his octogenarian mother-in-law, and people across the country 
reported similar conversations. In October, Rep. Robert Wexler, 
D-Fla., lamented that Clinton and the Lewinsky scandal ``cheapened 
our national discourse, confused our children, disillusioned our 
idealists and empowered our cynics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And, 22 years after Jimmy Carter was castigated for simply  
admitting he looked at women with ``lust in my heart,'' people 
wondered: Have the moral standards of leaders plummeted, or are we 
merely discussing this stuff openly for the first time? 
</P>
<P>
	``The major thing that has changed is that we've pulled back the  
curtain from leadership. And leadership needs that curtain,'' says 
Joe Klein, political writer for The New Yorker and author of 
``Primary Colors,'' the controversial novel based loosely on 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Great leaders are marbled like great steaks. There is fat and  
there is muscle, and the two are intertwined,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other arguments: that the whole mess shoved the  
shadowy interplay between vice and leadership into the public 
arena; that it turned the president into a real person rather than 
an ideal; that it proved the American public is smart enough to 
recognize a person's weaknesses and still deem him capable of 
leading. 
</P>
<P>
	That wasn't the case 11 years ago, when Gary Hart was forced  
from the 1988 presidential race after revelations about an affair. 
Now, attitudes toward public figures' sexual peccadillos have 
evolved into something more calloused or more open-minded, 
depending on your perspective. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has made it easier for any politician, for any public  
figure in the future to have their private sex lives publicly 
exposed and get away with it. The bar has been raised in terms of 
what it will take to shock the public,'' says Larry Tye, the 
biographer of public-relations pioneer Edward Bernays, widely 
considered the father of modern ``spin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So the contradiction remains: a nation of people saying they're  
weary of such matters, then continuing the discussion at every 
turn. People trying to make decisions about their leaders while 
calculating the boundaries of public and private after a wrenching 
year of shifting rhetorical terrain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's as if Clinton has let sex out of the closet. He's  
revealed to us more about ourselves than he ever intended to,'' 
says Kerry Walters, author of a new biography on Benjamin Franklin, 
himself a target of sexual misconduct allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've blended everything up in the same pot, and we don't know  
what to do with it. Pandora's Box has been opened. In terms of the 
`national dialogue,' there's no going back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
