<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada, U.S. in Magazine Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Describing the United States as a bully, Canadian  
officials say they are ready to risk a trade war rather than 
abandon a bill aimed at restricting U.S. magazine operations in 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade Minister Sergio Marchi, in an interview Monday with  
several American journalists, said the United States was out of 
line in threatening to retaliate against Canadian steel and textile 
exports if the magazine bill is passed. 
</P>
<P>
	Marchi characterized the U.S. attitude as ``I don't like this.  
Let me push you around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``That's simply not good enough,'' he said. ``You're the only  
superpower left in the world, but you're not the leader of the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would penalize foreign publishers that sell space to  
Canadian advertisers in special Canadian editions of their 
magazines. Canadian officials and publishers say these so-called 
split-run magazines would take ad revenue away from Canadian 
magazines, offering much cheaper ad rates because their editorial 
costs are covered by their home-country operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Heritage Minister Sheila Copps, who oversees Canada's cultural  
industries, says the bill should be passed by the House of Commons 
by early April. 
</P>
<P>
	She has urged the Americans to offer alternative proposals for  
protecting Canada's magazine industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``But, please, we will not bend to bullies,'' she said in a  
television interview Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Canadian officials trying to resolve the dispute have a  
third round of talks scheduled for Friday in Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	Marchi suggested the United States might be reluctant to soften  
its stance because it does not want to set a precedent that would 
encourage other countries to restrict U.S. cultural products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pop culture is one of the largest exports the Americans  
have,'' Marchi said. ``The Americans are looking at larger field, 
with possibly a slippery slope starting to disrupt this field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because of its proximity to the United States, Canada has a  
constant struggle trying to keep its cultural sectors vibrant in 
the face of massive competition from south of the border. Canadian 
films account for less than 5 percent of the national box office, 
and most of the top-rated prime time TV programs are American. 
</P>
<P>
	Marchi said magazines are even more vulnerable than other  
cultural sectors. Canadian singers, he noted, can succeed abroad, 
but Canadian magazines are unlikely to find readers except at home. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian officials say Canada already has one of the most open  
magazine markets anywhere, with U.S. and other foreign magazines 
accounting for about 80 percent of newsstand sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The pending bill would not prevent such magazines from  
circulating in Canada. It would simply bar Canadian companies from 
advertising in them. The bill would exempt a handful of split-runs 
that have been publishing in Canada for many years, such as the 
Canadian edition Time. 
</P>
<P>
	Canada previously restricted split-runs with a high tax on their  
revenues. That measure was struck down by the World Trade 
Organization in 1997, prompting the government to draft the pending 
bill as an alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	While Canadian publishers strongly support the bill, the  
Association of Canadian Advertisers opposes it as an unwarranted 
restriction of free enterprise. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky has denounced the  
bill as ```protectionist and discriminatory.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
