<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin's Impeachment Hearings End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A parliamentary committee seeking to impeach Boris  
Yeltsin finished its work Monday and began preparing a motion to 
remove him from office, a move that is expected to fail. 
</P>
<P>
	Vadim Filimonov, the Communist Party member who led the  
impeachment hearings, said leaders of the parliament's lower house 
will receive the commission's findings Thursday and the entire body 
will probably begin reviewing the motion in two weeks, the Interfax 
news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The impeachment commission, set up last summer, says Yeltsin  
should be held accountable for instigating the 1991 Soviet 
collapse; using force against hard-line lawmakers in 1993; 
launching the botched war in Chechnya; bringing the nation's 
military to ruin; and committing ``genocide'' against the Russian 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The motion to oust Yeltsin must win a two-thirds majority in the  
lower house, which is considered unlikely. Then it would face the 
Constitutional and Supreme Courts and would have to win passage in 
the upper house of Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, Yeltsin dismissed Russia's migration service chief,  
Tatyana Regent; the presidential envoy to several Caucasus regions, 
Pyotr Marchenko; and the head of the State Cinematography 
Committee, Armen Medvedev. 
</P>
<P>
	The presidential press service, which reported the dismissals,  
gave the standard explanations, saying the three were let go at 
their ``own wish,'' to transfer to another job, or for retirement. 
It provided no details. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Deputy Finance Minister Oleg Vyugin said one or two  
experts from the International Monetary Fund will arrive Wednesday, 
despite earlier government statements that a full mission would 
return to Russia this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't rule out the possibility that an IMF mission could  
visit Moscow by the end of the month, but we must work through 
certain budget issues first,'' Vyugin said, according to Interfax. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has urged the IMF to release new loans so that the  
government can pay off part of its massive domestic and foreign 
debts. The IMF has remained noncommittal, demanding that the 
Cabinet approve a viable economic plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Vyugin said the IMF had sent a letter analyzing the government's  
latest economic proposals but refused to comment on its contents. 
The IMF has criticized this year's budget as unrealistic and 
insists the government further cut spending and take stronger 
action to boost revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	It has specifically assailed the government's plan to cut taxes,  
a move intended to help Russia's ailing industries. The IMF said 
the tax cuts would only further erode already scarce revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	In what appeared an attempt to please the IMF, the Finance  
Ministry on Monday said the government would ask parliament to 
delay a planned cut in the value-added tax until as late as July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
