<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Victor G. Bloede    	
</P>
<P>
	BOYNTON BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Victor G. Bloede, a former  
advertising executive whose love for words helped create memorable 
campaigns for Maxwell House coffee, Conoco Oil and Crest 
toothpaste, died Wednesday. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloede served as chairman and chief executive of Benton &AMP; Bowles  
Advertising, a large international agency he rebuilt during his 33 
years with the company. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the ad agency in 1950 as a copywriter, worked his way  
up to vice president five years later and became president and 
chief executive by 1968. Three years later he became chairman, a 
position he held until he retired in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloede helped introduce the Maxwell House slogan: ``Good to the  
last drop'' and the Conoco Oil slogan: ``The hottest brand going.'' 
He helped Proctor &AMP; Gamble with its ``Please don't squeeze the 
Charmin'' slogan for its toilet tissue and was instrumental in 
helping the company establish Crest as a leading toothpaste. 
</P>
<P>
	Benton &AMP; Bowles later merged with D'Arcy, Masius to become  
D'Arcy, Masius, Benton &AMP; Bowles. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jaki Byard    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jaki Byard, a pianist, saxophonist and music  
teacher who recorded with modern-jazz artists Charles Mingus and 
Rahasaan Roland Kirk, was found shot dead at his Queens home on 
Thursday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Police were investigating the shooting, which went unheard by  
Byard's family members, said one of his two daughters, Denise 
Byard-Mitchell. 
</P>
<P>
	Byard's playing spanned the history of jazz. His improvisations  
included boogie-woogie and free jazz with zippy stylistic changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Byard taught for several decades and was instrumental in the  
re-evaluation of jazz history that began in the late 1970s. Early 
in his career he was a big player in the Boston jazz scene. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1960s, Byard began recording with Mingus. He played  
on the classic albums ``Mingus Mingus Mingus Mingus Mingus'' and 
``The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Duke Ellington became sick just before he died, Byard  
played piano in the Ellington Orchestra. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Harry A. Cole    	
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Retired Judge Harry A. Cole, the first black to  
serve on the state's highest court and the first elected to the 
state Senate, died Sunday of complications from pneumonia. He was 
78. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole became the first black to win a state Senate seat in 1954.  
In 1977, he was the first black named to the Maryland Court of 
Appeals, where he served until his retirement in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	During his 14-year tenure on the court, Cole wrote the unanimous  
opinion that upheld the right of the state to fund abortions for 
poor women. 
</P>
<P>
	He served in World War II in the Army, serving in Europe and the  
Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole was hired as an assistant state attorney general in 1953,  
becoming the first black lawyer to work in the office. He became 
Maryland's first black state senator by defeating incumbent state 
Sen. Bernard S. Melnicove by 37 votes. He served one term, losing 
by 2,000 votes four years later. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Jimmy Dudley    	
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Jimmy Dudley, the radio voice of the  
Cleveland Indians from 1948, the year the team won its last World 
Series, until 1967, died following a stroke Friday in Tucson, Ariz. 
He was 89 and had Alzheimer's disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley was inducted into the broadcasters' wing of the Baseball  
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	After apprenticing as an announcer for the Chicago Cubs after  
the war, he was hired by the Indians. He also did play-by-play for 
the Cleveland Browns in the 1950s, for the Baltimore Colts and for 
Ohio State University football games. 
</P>
<P>
	He became the voice of the Seattle Pilots in 1969, but a year  
later, the team transferred to Milwaukee, leaving him behind. 
Dudley never announced a major league game again. His wife said his 
last trip to Cleveland was in 1993, when the Indians played their 
final games in Cleveland Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his wife of 49 years, Angie, Dudley is survived by a  
son, a daughter, two grandchildren and a brother. 

</P>
<P>
                         *William T. Fields    	
</P>
<P>
	TUPELO, Miss. (AP) -- Financial consultant William T. Fields,  
founder of the telecommunications company that evolved into 
industry giant MCI-WorldCom, died Saturday of pancreatic cancer. He 
was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields was best known for his role in founding Long Distance  
Discount Service in June 1984. He was one of nine original 
investors in the company that took advantage of AT&AMP;T's divestiture 
of its Bell companies in the early 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally formed as a telephone equipment company, LDDS soon  
grew into a long-distance company. Fields was named the company's 
first chief executive officer and was chairman of the board. 
</P>
<P>
	After less than a year at the helm, Fields turned over the  
company's operations to a hand-picked successor, Bernie Ebbers. The 
company has since become MCI-WorldCom, which is now second only to 
AT&AMP;T as the world's largest telecommunications company. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Bradford Grow    	
</P>
<P>
	O'FALLON, Ill. (AP) -- Bradford Grow, retired pioneer of naval  
aviation and decorated veteran of the Guadalcanal campaign, died 
Thursday. He was 99. 
</P>
<P>
	Grow, a retired rear admiral, graduated from the Naval Academy  
in 1922 and began his flying career four years later. 
</P>
<P>
	A highlight of Grow's aviation career came in 1939, when he led  
a squadron of amphibious planes on a round-trip flight between San 
Diego and Panama without refueling to demonstrate the aircraft's 
capabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II, Grow commanded aircraft carriers, including  
the USS Kasaan Bay and the USS Lexington, in the Pacific and 
European theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	At Guadalcanal, Grow presided over the calm evacuation of the  
USS Wasp as it sank under enemy fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Grow's World War II honors are the Bronze Star, the Legion  
of Merit and the French Croix de Guerre. He retired from the Navy 
in 1952. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Prasit Kanchanawat    	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Prasit Kanchanawat, a prominent  
politician in the bloody upheaval that rocked Thailand in the 
1970s, died Sunday of cancer. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	A commoner who served in both military and civilian governments,  
Prasit was a lawyer and banker before becoming a member of 
parliament in 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	Prasit held several high-level economic posts in the 1960s  
before becoming commerce minister in 1972 under the premiership of 
Field Marshal Thanom Kittakchorn. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanom's government was overthrown in a mass uprising against  
military rule in 1973. A fragile experiment with democracy ensued. 
</P>
<P>
	Prasit was speaker of the first -- though short-lived -- elected  
parliament in 1975. New elections in April 1976 led to Seni Pramoj, 
leader of Thai resistance against Japanese occupation in World War 
II, becoming prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Prasit was justice minister in Seni's government, which fell in  
October 1976 as the military and right-wing extremists massacred 
leftist students and staged a coup. 
</P>
<P>
	The coup ended Prasit's political career. In later years, he 	
served on the board of directors of Bangkok Bank, Thailand's 
largest financial institution. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Max Samter 	
</P>
<P>
	EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) -- Dr. Max Samter, a leader in the treatment  
of people with allergies who was known for his groundbreaking 
textbook on immunology, died Tuesday at the age of 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter was the first to recognize that patients who had both  
asthma and nasal polyps, a severe inflammation of the tissue lining 
the nose or sinuses, could have a dangerous reaction to aspirin. 
Such patients are now said to have Samter's syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter was president of the American Academy of Allergy, Asthma  
and Immunology in 1958-59 and helped establish the International 
Association of Allergology in the 1950s. He retired from the 
University of Illinois in 1975 but continued to treat patients 
until 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter's book, Immunological Diseases, was called the first  
comprehensive text in the field. He wrote it in the 1950s and saw 
it through four editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Samter fled Germany in 1937 after he wrote several short novels  
satirizing the Nazis. He served as a doctor in the U.S. Army during 
World War II, when he developed concussive deafness. 
</P>
<P>
	He was advised to give up any plans for a clinical practice  
because of the ailment, but resumed treating patients when his 
deafness did not progress as quickly as had been feared. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Cecil Smith    	
</P>
<P>
	BOERNE, Texas (AP) -- Cecil Smith, a polo player who won  
virtually every award the sport offers and propelled the 
competition from amateur to international status in a career 
spanning more than six decades, died Jan. 21. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Often referred to by writers as the ``Babe Ruth of polo,'' Smith  
won every major U.S. high-goal tournament of his time. He was 
inducted into the Texas Sports Hall of Fame in 1956 and was one of 
the first six players to be elected to the Polo Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith began his polo career in 1924 in the Texas Hill Country.  
By 1930, he was an alternate on the U.S. international team. In 
1938 and for the next decade, he was a 10-goal player, the sport's 
highest ranking and one achieved by only 20 American-born players. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's 1938 Texas Ranger team was the only foursome to win  
every major tournament in England. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Irwin C. Watson    	
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Irwin C. ``Watty'' Watson, a comedian and  
musician who appeared in nightclubs and on television, stage and 
cruise ships, died of a heart attack Feb. 1. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson played at nightclubs around New York City and hotels in  
the Catskill Mountains. Besides the saxophone, he also played 
trumpet, violin, piano and clarinet. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1950s and '60s, Watson frequently appeared on  
television and the stage. He was a comedy star on ``That Was The 
Week That Was'' with David Frost; a regular on the ``Tonight Show'' 
with Johnny Carson; and appeared with Ed Sullivan, Steve Allen, 
Virginia Graham, Mike Douglas and on other shows. 
</P>
<P>
	At various times, Watson was the opening act for stars including  
Sammy Davis Jr., Paul Anka, Duke Ellington, Cab Calloway and Aretha 
Franklin. 
</P>
<P>
	During the last 15 years he entertained on cruise liners  
traveling the world. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Doug Weston    	
</P>
<P>
	WEST HOLLYWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Doug Weston, founder of the  
nightclub Troubadour that showcased such folk, rock and comedy acts 
as Joan Baez, Elton John and Lenny Bruce, died Sunday after a short 
battle with pneumonia. He was 72 and had been hospitalized with 
pneumonia since Feb. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston prided himself in the acts and audiences he attracted for  
more than four decades, from singer Linda Ronstadt to comedians 
such as the Smothers Brothers and Cheech &AMP; Chong. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1960s and early 1970s, the Troubadour was considered  
the most consistently important showcase of contemporary folk and 
folk-rock talent in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearances there could guarantee major record sales for new and  
emerging artists. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the club's acts were consistently impressive:  
the Byrds, Judy Collins, Bill Cosby, the Committee, Bo Diddley, 
Arlo Guthrie, Richie Havens, Gordon Lightfoot, Roger Miller, Joni 
Mitchell, Laura Nyro, Mort Sahl, Kris Kristofferson and Nina 
Simone. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston first set up shop in the 1950s in a 65-seat coffeehouse  
on La Cienega Boulevard. By 1957 he had made enough money to open 
the 300-seat Troubadour in West Hollywood. 


</P>
</TEXT>
