<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn. Bridges Can Salt Themselves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRWIN, Pa. (AP) -- If everything works right, motorists will  
never have to wait for road crews to salt three bridges in western 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Before snow falls on any of the overpasses, weather sensors will  
anticipate the precipitation and spray the roads with magnesium 
chloride, which is essentially liquid salt. 
</P>
<P>
	The spray should save time for road crews and keep the roadways  
clear for drivers. A bridge generally freezes faster than a road 
because cold air passes both above and beneath the span. 
</P>
<P>
	The de-icing systems on the Pennsylvania bridges are the only  
three of their kind in the United States, said Mike Strobel, who 
spent Monday putting the finishing touches on the U.S. Route 30 
overpass near Irwin, about 15 miles southeast of Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	If the sensors and low-lying salters work, Pennsylvania  
Department of Transportation officials plan to use them around the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the future,'' said Strobel, manager of the project for  
Boschung Co. 
</P>
<P>
	The Route 30 equipment passed its first test Sunday night. A  
second bridge has had the technology for about two weeks and work 
on a third bridge should be complete in the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
	The equipment for all three bridges cost about $550,000,  
Transportation Department spokesman Steve Chizmar said. 
</P>
<P>
	The handful of other U.S. bridges with salt sprayers have  
equipment that is activated by people, Chizmar said. The 
Pennsylvania bridges are unique because they work without human 
help, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	One set of sensors tracks air temperature, wind speed and  
direction, humidity and other weather data, Chizmar said. Other 
sensors measure the pavement temperature and calculate how much 
salt is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	The technology has been used for years in parts of Europe, said  
Strobel, whose company is based in Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
