<DOCNO> APW19990215.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 22:42:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polls Powerful in Impeachment Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky and President Clinton's  
impeachment put the spotlight on polls and the pressure on 
pollsters as never before, and public opinion proved powerful. 
</P>
<P>
	When news of the investigation by Independent Counsel Kenneth  
Starr of the president's relationship with Ms. Lewinsky broke in 
January 1998, several political analysts said Clinton would never 
survive politically. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, some predicted the public would turn on the president  
once the accusations were proven true. By fall, many forecast the 
Republicans would steamroll Democrats in November's congressional 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The American public had other ideas.  
</P>
<P>
	They gave the president some of the highest job approval ratings  
of his presidency, in the 60s through much of the year as the 
economy flourished. And a solid majority opposed his removal. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was one of the strongest reaffirmations of democracy I  
have seen,'' said Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, general chairman of the 
Democratic Party. ``People got it right, got it early and they 
stayed with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At first, many people were skeptical about the charges against  
Clinton, but about half said he should be impeached if he lied 
under oath about his affair with Ms. Lewinsky. Later, the number in 
favor of impeachment settled at about one in three. 
</P>
<P>
	Pollsters repeated their questions frequently, anticipating that  
people would turn against the president at some point. 
</P>
<P>
	It never happened.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans had a tougher year. They lost five House seats in  
mid-term elections. House Speaker Newt Gingrich resigned. Then Rep. 
Bob Livingston, the speaker-designate, quit after his own 
infidelity was disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The year was humbling for pundits and pollsters too, Republican  
pollster Bill McInturff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Who would have guessed a year ago, he said, that ``the president  
wouldn't be removed but it would wipe out the Republican 
leadership?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In general, the American electorate has shown a tolerance for  
personal behavior,'' McInturff added, ``that is far wider and 
broader than I would have imagined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As Republicans pushed ahead with impeachment, they repeatedly  
said the polls were not a principal concern. But Republicans found 
some poll results worth noting, citing results that highlighted the 
majority of Americans who thought Clinton lied under oath and 
didn't trust him personally. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's been too much focus on the polls and not enough on  
what's right and on principle,'' said Republican National Committee 
spokesman Mike Collins. ``If we were interested in doing the 
political thing, we would have dropped this months ago. We were 
following principle and doing our duty under the Constitution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The polls proved powerful because they gave a clear and  
recurring message, said Robert Shapiro, a Columbia University 
political scientist who studies public opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Different organizations were asking the same kinds of  
questions and finding the same patterns and trends,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the president's ratings on handling of his job were low or  
the economy had gone bad, ``he'd be gone,'' Shapiro said. 
</P>
<P>
	By the closing days of the impeachment process, some Republicans  
acknowledged their unsuccessful bid to oust Clinton had hurt them 
in the polls. But they predicted they would have time to recover 
and focus on tax cuts and other popular issues before the 2000 
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
