<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Feb. 15, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Meets With Mexico's Zedillo  
</P>
<P>
	MERIDA, Mexico (AP) -- President Clinton and Mexican President  
Ernesto Zedillo met today to discuss such things as trade and drugs 
just two weeks before Clinton must make a formal evaluation of 
Mexico's cooperation in trying to shut down the narcotics trade. 
Answering Mexican and U.S. congressional complaints that the 
current process is vague, one-sided and political, Clinton and 
Zedillo outlined today 16 measures -- including U.S. demands for a 
reduction in drugs and extraditions by Mexico -- by which 
performance will be judged. On another subject, with the 
impeachment cloud lifted, Clinton said he would seek cooperation 
with Republicans in Congress who tried to remove him from office. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Warplanes Strike Sites in Iraq  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. warplanes struck at Iraqi defense sites  
on two separate occasions today, responding to Iraqi challenges in 
the northern ``no fly'' zone, a Defense Department spokesman said. 
Two F-15E's were fired upon by an antiaircraft artillery site north 
of Mosul, which is some 250 miles north of Baghdad, Lt. Col. Steve 
Campbell said. In response, one of the fighter planes dropped a 
500-pound bomb on the site. The fighter planes returned undamaged 
to their base in Incirlik, southern Turkey, U.S. officials said. In 
a separate confrontation, another U.S. warplane launched a missile 
at an Iraqi radar site that had targeted it about an hour later, 
Campbell said. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain Artillery Slated for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- The British army began moving military  
vehicles and heavy guns from Germany to Greece today for use in a 
possible NATO intervention in Kosovo. About 400 vehicles, including 
tanks and armored infantry vehicles, were loaded onto ferries in 
the northern port of Emden for transport to Thessalonika, the army 
said. Meanwhile, outside Paris, where talks to try to end the 
Serbian-Kosovo Albanian fighting, the United States and five other 
nations have given rival Serbs and ethnic Albanians until noon 
Saturday to consider a plan for ending yearlong conflict, Kosovo, 
but hurdles remain. 

</P>
<P>
	American Seeks Return to Normal  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- American Airlines officials think they might  
resume regular service as early as tomorrow as more and more pilots 
end their sick-out. About 800 of American's 9,400 pilots were still 
listed as sick today, compared to the nearly 2,500 who declared 
themselves unfit to fly Thursday and Friday, American officials 
said. However, about 250 -- or roughly 11 percent -- of the 2,250 
flights scheduled for today have been canceled because some pilots 
weren't immediately available for flying. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich To Run for President  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House  
Budget Committee and a champion of tax cuts, laid the groundwork 
today for a longshot presidential campaign based on returning 
``power to the people.'' A crowd of 300 turned out in his adopted 
hometown for a $100-a-person breakfast this morning. Kasich, a 
nine-term Republican congressman announced his plans to file papers 
with the Federal Election Commission to formally establish a 
presidential exploratory committee. 

</P>
<P>
	Islamic Militant Arrested in Paris  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- An Islamic militant believed linked to Osama bin  
Laden, the suspected mastermind of deadly U.S. embassy bombings in 
Africa, has been arrested in France, police said today. Said 
Laidoni was arrested at Paris' Gare du Nord train station on Jan. 
18 by members of France's internal security service, known as the 
DST. He was charged with criminal association with a terrorist 
enterprise, police and judicial sources said. The sources spoke on 
condition of anonymity. The DST insisted Laidoni ``has no direct 
link'' with last year's bombings of the U.S. embassies in Kenya and 
Tanzania. 

</P>
<P>
	Marv Albert Signs With Turner Sports  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Marv Albert is joining Turner Sports to do NBA  
games and other sports, moving his return to broadcasting to the 
national level. Albert, fired by NBC in 1997 after pleading guilty 
to biting a woman during a sexual encounter in a Virginia hotel 
room, agreed to a multiyear contract and was introduced as a Turner 
Sports announcer today at Madison Square Garden. 

</P>
