<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Epic Honor Wins Golden State Mile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN MATEO, Calif. (AP) -- Epic Honor had no room to run on the  
far turn. Instead, the colt found some in the stretch, getting the 
lead with an explosive move to win Monday's $100,000 Golden State 
Mile at Bay Meadows. 
</P>
<P>
	``He finished like gangbusters! I think we'll move on to the  
list of Kentucky Derby contenders now,'' said Phil Lebherz, a 
co-owner of the 3-year-old Epic Honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinned between horses at the three-eighths pole, Epic Honor's  
jockey, Lonnie Meche, had to pull back the reins and check him, 
forcing the colt to lose momentum. 
</P>
<P>
	Meche then altered course, dropping from the outside to the  
rail, where he squeezed past tiring horses before an astonishing 
burst carried him past pacesetting Brave Gun for a three-length 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact he was able to get stood up on his ear, regroup and  
come back to win was the most impressive part of the race to me,'' 
said Jeff Bonde, Epic Honor's trainer. ``He's showing more and more 
seasoning. It looks like he'll run anywhere now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The owners definitely have derby fever and I'd like to go,  
too, if the horse shows me he's good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meche, who has never had a Kentucky Derby mount, said Epic Honor  
was making a strong case for a Triple Crown campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a real tough trip and he overcame a lot of trouble,  
that's for sure. A lot of horses wouldn't have been able to do what 
he did today. He's been doing everything a horse could possibly to 
make it to the derby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Epic Honor covered the mile in 1:36.76, earned $55,000 for his  
owners, and returned $6.80 to win, $5.60 to place and $9.40 to 
show. Brave Gun hung on for second and paid $7 to place and $13.80 
to show while longshot Sixoutasix returned $20.20. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual show pool payout was due to the triple-entry of High  
Noon Meeting, Voice of Destiny and Absolute Harmony finishing out 
of the money. The three, bet as a single entry, had gone off as the 
odds-on favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	Epic Honor, who has three wins in eight career starts and has  
never run worse than third, boosted his lifetime earnings to 
$194,850. The colt, pointing toward a Triple Crown campaign, has 
won stakes in each of his last two starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonde said Epic Honor would run next in either the $200,000 El  
Camino Real Derby on March 6 at Bay Meadows or the $750,000 Gallery 
Furniture.com Stakes at Turfway Park in Kentucky on March 27. The 
Kentucky Derby will be run May 1 at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
