<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lady Vols Stay No. 1 in AP Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Opponents might be getting the idea that the way to play  
Tennessee is to slow it down. 
</P>
<P>
	Let them try, coach Pat Summitt said.  
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's last two opponents have tried to control the tempo,  
but the Lady Vols beat them both and Monday, they remained an 
overwhelming choice as the No. 1 team in The Associated Press 
women's basketball poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn gave Tennessee a tough game Sunday before the Lady Vols  
prevailed 71-63. Vanderbilt also played at a controlled pace the 
week before. and Tennessee won 66-60. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's something I'm sure people will look at and say  
maybe we do want to change our approach,'' Summitt said. 
``Fortunately, we've been in that situation enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday, our players did not seem to get rattled at all with  
it,'' she said. ``They just kept their consistency and their 
composure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With its swift, multi-talented athletes, Tennessee prefers to  
get into a running game. And when teams try to run with the Lady 
Vols, they usually get run over. Before beating Vanderbilt, 
Tennessee had routed Mississippi 96-58 and Mississippi State 94-53. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee often can pick up the tempo with its defense, forcing  
turnovers that lead to quick baskets. But if the Lady Vols are 
forced into a half-court game, Summitt feels her three-time 
defending national champions can handle it. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're certainly better prepared than we were a year ago,'' she  
said. ``We've been in that situation more this year. Quite 
honestly, last year I thought more people would attempt to play us 
the way Vanderbilt, Alabama and Auburn played us. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect to see it more as we close out the season and get  
into the postseason,'' Summitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee (23-1) received 40 of 41 first-place votes and 1,024  
points from a national media panel to lead the poll for the sixth 
straight week. No. 2 Purdue and No. 3 Louisiana Tech both held 
their positions, but there was considerable shuffling after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven teams from the Top 25 lost during the past week,  
including four in the Top 10, but seven were beaten by other ranked 
teams and no one dropped from the poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue (23-1) received the other first-place vote and had 981  
points. The Boilermakers had to come from behind to win at Penn 
State in overtime, then routed Ohio State at home. Louisiana Tech 
(20-2) beat a Top 25 team, Florida International, on the road and 
received 947 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado State (26-1) moved up one spot to fourth and was  
followed by Old Dominion, Connecticut, Rutgers, Duke, Notre Dame 
and Virginia Tech, which made the Top 10 for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Dominion jumped three places to its highest ranking of the  
season after beating Connecticut, which dropped two spots. Rutgers 
climbed two places following a victory over Notre Dame, which went 
from sixth to ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	The No. 7 ranking was the highest for Rutgers since it was sixth  
the week of Jan. 14, 1991. Duke fell one spot to eighth after its 
first Atlantic Coast Conference loss, 80-75 at Clemson. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas Tech climbed two places to 11th, North Carolina was 12th,  
UCLA 13th and Clemson and Georgia were tied for 14th. Georgia fell 
four places after losing to unranked Vanderbilt. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State was 16th, followed by Virginia, Oregon, Iowa State  
and UC Santa Barbara. Kansas, Auburn, Florida International, LSU 
and Alabama held the five final spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn also lost to Alabama last week and fell five places for  
the biggest drop in the poll. Clemson's move from 19th to 14th and 
Oregon's from 23rd to 18th were the biggest jumps. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemson beat Georgia Tech by 28 before knocking off Duke, while  
Oregon defeated Washington State and Washington to pull into a 
first-place tie with UCLA in the Pac-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
