<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus surged nearly 40 percent last  
year to a record high, further diminishing hopes that Asia's 
largest economy will act as a buyer of last resort for goods 
produced in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's current account surplus, the broadest measure of trade,  
surged 38.7 percent to an unprecedented 15.86 trillion yen ($139.18 
billion) in 1998, the Finance Ministry announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharp increase comes amid growing pressure on Japan to  
revive its sluggish economy and import more goods as a way to help 
its struggling neighbors in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures -- which measure trade in merchandise, services,  
tourism and investment -- are calculated by taking the difference 
between Japan's income from foreign sources against payments on 
foreign obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports tumbled 11.7 percent to $288.43 billion while exports  
fell only 1.3 percent to $428.81 billion for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous record was a surplus of $128.72 billion for 1993.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan's current account surplus also rose for the month of  
December, gaining 13.3 percent from the same month a year earlier 
to $12.79 billion. Both imports and exports fell in December but 
the surplus grew because imports fell faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports from Japan fell 12.9 percent to $34.90 billion, while  
imports dropped 23.3 percent to $21.20 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
