<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expectations High as Yanks Open Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- The challenge awaiting the New York Yankees  
can be seen on the back of the Legends Field scoreboard in big and 
bold letters. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a sign welcoming fans to the spring home of the 1998 World  
Series champions: ``The best team ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Against the backdrop of their 125-win season, the Yankees open  
spring training Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``At times, it seemed almost like an out-of-body experience,''  
vice president of player development Mark Newman said. ``You kept 
thinking something has got to end ... the Yankees can't win that 
many games. It was an eerie experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York went 114-48 during the regular season, setting an AL  
record for wins, then went 11-2 in the postseason, including a 
World Series sweep of San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The only player not back is outfielder Tim Raines, who signed  
with Oakland. The pressure to repeat last year's results will be 
staring at all the rest as they try to win their third Series title 
in four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an honor to be a part of that team because it's going to  
be compared to the greatest teams of all-time'' shortstop Derek 
Jeter said. ``After my first year (the 1996 world champion season), 
people were saying what can you do to top that. Once you win, you 
get spoiled and want to keep winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York entered the offseason unsure of its future roster. But  
owner George Steinbrenner re-signed center fielder Bernie Williams 
($87.5 million for seven years), pitcher David Cone ($8 million for 
one year) and third baseman Scott Brosius ($15.75 million for three 
years), and exercised a $3.4 million option on catcher Joe Girardi. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our organization did a great job keeping everybody together  
and giving us another chance to win the World Series,'' first 
baseman Tino Martinez said. ``We've got a new year coming up and 
hopefully we can win the World Series again and match last year if 
we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees starting lineup appears set, except for what has  
become an annual battle for the left-field spot. Darryl Strawberry, 
who had a cancerous tumor removed from his colon last October, will 
be competing with Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee and Shane Spencer. 
</P>
<P>
	Although starters Cone (36) and David Wells (35) are a year  
older, the pitching staff remains potent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody has an 0-and-0 record,'' Newman said, looking ahead  
to the start of formal workouts Thursday. ``The teams that didn't 
do well last year are buoyed by the hope that they will improve. 
And those that did well, us in particular, are concerned about 
repeating.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
