<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jokes Have Always Filled Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George Washington had no sooner dipped a  
silver trowel in mortar to lay the Capitol cornerstone than the 
city he founded became the butt of scoffers, cynics and scolds. 
</P>
<P>
	``A monument raised to a deceased project,'' Charles Dickens  
huffed in 1842. ``Grand, gloomy and peculiar,'' another writer 
mused in 1848. ``A vast practical joke,'' an exasperated English 
newspaper correspondent sputtered during the Civil War. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints about the city of Washington and those who govern  
here started early and have never ceased. 
</P>
<P>
	The scornful at first directed their needles at the puffed-up  
pretentiousness of a 10-mile-square patch of brush and swamp, with 
an unfinished, domeless Capitol and virtually no creature comforts, 
claiming itself as the capital of a self-respecting nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Boosters envisioned the reincarnation of ancient Rome.  
Detractors saw the city as a mouse with delusions of grandeur. 
</P>
<P>
	``This embryo Capital, where Fancy sees, squares in morasses,  
obelisks in trees,'' declaimed visiting English poet Thomas Moore 
in 1806, six years after the government moved in. 
</P>
<P>
	Created expressly as a federal district apart from any state,  
Washington had no past, hardly any present and an extremely cloudy 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	As the city's first century unreeled and Washington City made  
itself an enduring fact, the complaints shifted to the character of 
the government the city housed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Persons who love dissipation, persons who love to watch the  
game of politics, and those who make a study of strong minds under 
great excitement like a season in Washington,'' travel writer 
Harriet Martineau asserted in 1838. 
</P>
<P>
	The British soldiers who torched the place in 1814 fanned the  
fires with derision. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. James Scott called the burned-out White House no great loss.  
It was, he declared, ``remarkable for nothing, except the want of 
taste.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city that rose from the fire got no slack from the travelers  
who followed the British army. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole affair ... looks as though some giant had scattered  
a lot of child's toys at random,'' Capt. Basil Hall wrote in 1827. 
``Everything wears the appearance of poverty and want of 
permanency,'' Charles Francis Adams told his diary seven years 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	``The town looks like a large straggling village reared in a  
drained swamp,'' said traveler George Combe in 1838. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Dickens, visiting in 1842, found the Capitol stained  
with the juice of chewed tobacco. The carpets were so drenched and 
filthy that anything dropped on them should be left there, even a 
wallet, he cautioned. 
</P>
<P>
	As to the place itself, Dickens wrote, it is ``a city of  
magnificent intentions,'' none of them realized. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington offers a clinching proof of the proposition that  
one cannot bring a great city into existence by mere will power,'' 
said French scientist Jean-Jacques Ampere in 1851. 
</P>
<P>
	The Civil War brought Washington danger and confusion and more  
complaints than ever: dust, dirt, squalor, noise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found the Capital still under the reign of King Mud ...,''  
British novelist Anthony Trollope wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``If one were to judge the American people by their capital, one  
would have a very poor opinion of them,'' a visiting Frenchman, 
Ernest Duvergier de Hauranne, said in 1864. 
</P>
<P>
	``Washington will be, I have no doubt, someday uproariously  
splendid, but at present it isn't anything. It is in the District 
of Columbia and the state of the future ...,'' George Agustus Sala, 
a correspondent for the London Telegraph, observed in 1865. 
</P>
<P>
	Sala emptied his bucket of disdain to produce this: ``a great,  
scrambling, slack-baked embryo of a city basking in the December 
sun like an alligator of a mud bank of a bayou in July.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By century's end the mud had dried and the government at  
Washington did its best to rule. 
</P>
<P>
	And the complaining continued.  
</P>
<P>
	``The progress of Evolution from President Washington to  
President Grant was alone evidence enough to upset Darwin,'' wrote 
Henry Adams, whose own family included the second and sixth 
presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	``My God! What is there in this place that a man should ever  
want to get into it?'' James Garfield asked in 1881. 
</P>
<P>
	Leave the last words to Mark Twain as Washington's first century  
ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``Suppose you were an idiot. And suppose you were a member of  
Congress. But I repeat myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House,  
Congress and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 17:42:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Father of Jets QB Testaverde Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Al Testaverde, who realized his lifelong dream  
when his son, Vinny, became the quarterback for the hometown New 
York Jets, has died of a heart attack in Florida. He was 66. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Testaverde was vacationing with his wife, Josie, in  
Fort Lauderdale, when he was stricken on Sunday, Jets spokesman 
Frank Ramos said. Ramos was unable to provide further details. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Testaverde was Vinny's best friend and biggest fan,  
celebrating the good times and the bad, from his son's Heisman 
Trophy season of 1986 at the University of Miami to the poor 
seasons toiling for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers. 
</P>
<P>
	This past season was the best of everything for the Testaverdes,  
who couldn't be prouder of their son after he stepped in as the 
Jets starting quarterback and nearly led them to the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	At 35, Vinny Testaverde, who dedicated his Heisman to his  
father, made the Pro Bowl and Big Al, as he was affectionately 
known, was the happiest man on the planet. 
</P>
<P>
	On visits to local restaurants in Elmont, N.Y., which lies in  
the shadow of Belmont Park, one of his favorite haunts, Al 
Testaverde always had a smile on his face when he talked about ``my 
Vincent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm so proud of him, words can't describe it,'' Big Al would  
say. ``I've been blessed to have such a wonderful son.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Al Testaverde was a regular at Jets training camp at Hofstra,  
about 20 minutes from his home, and often drove his son home for 
lunch and dinner. The license plates on Al's car read 
``HEISMAN86.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Al appeared on the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show'' to talk  
about his son's success. 
</P>
<P>
	Al Testaverde had a history of heart problems, though. He  
suffered a heart attack at Tampa Stadium in 1987, and hadn't 
watched his son play a game in person since. He would watch tapes 
of the games, but only after he found out the score. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Jets were winning the AFC East, though, Big Al was  
tempted to go to a game but knew his doctors wouldn't allow it. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before the Jets played Denver in the AFC title, he said  
he'd go to Miami for the Super Bowl if the Jets were in it. Denver 
won 23-10, but Vinny Testaverde was the talk of the town as he 
compiled a 13-2 record after replacing Glenn Foley as the Jets 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Vinny makes it to the Super Bowl, I'll go to the game in  
Miami,' ' Al Testaverde had told The Journal News recently. ``If 
I'm going to die, that would be the way I'd want to go, with a 
smile, watching my son pay in the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like my life has been fulfilled. Everything I've wished  
for my son this season has come true. I feel as if I've won 20 
Super Bowls because of the character Vinny's shown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vinny Testaverde flew from his home in Tampa, Fla., to handle  
funeral arrangements. A private wake will be held Tuesday and 
Wednesday for family and friends and funeral services will be 
Thursday at undisclosed sites in Elmont, where the Testaverdes 
lived for the past 32 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides his son and wife, Al Testaverde is survived by four  
daughters and 10 grandchildren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 00:23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Draws Denmark in Women's Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Even as the matches for the Women's  
World Cup this summer were being set, organizers were pleading with 
fans around the country to show their support for the biggest 
women-only sporting event in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``Come this summer and fill the stadiums and excite young girls  
all over the world,'' said Donna de Varona, chair of the organizing 
committee for the 32-match tournament that will run from June 
19-July 10 in seven U.S. cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States drew North Korea, Nigeria and Denmark in its  
group for first-round matches. The Americans have six wins and a 
tie in their 10 games against Denmark, while the U.S. squad has 
never played North Korea or Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could call this the unknown group, because we really don't  
know North Korea or Nigeria very well,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco 
said after Sunday night's draw. ``Denmark has been a strong, 
physical opponent for us in the past, and will be a good test for 
us in the opener.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffeny Milbrett, a forward on the U.S. team, said the Americans  
are more comfortable with Denmark than with the other nations in 
their group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I am a little scared of unknown teams,'' Milbrett  
said. ``Often those types of teams are scrappy teams. And scrappy 
teams' strengths tend to match up against our weaknesses pretty 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draw resulted in confusion about which nation the Americans  
will play in their opening match, and got more confusing when 
officials switched around two groups for marketing reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	FIFA president Sepp Blatter announced during the draw ceremony,  
televised live throughout the United States, that the U.S. team 
will face North Korea in its opening match June 19 at Giants 
Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	But Women's World Cup officials later said the U.S. team will  
face Denmark in that opening match. The Americans will play Nigeria 
at Chicago's Soldier Field on June 24 and complete their 
first-round matches against North Korea at Foxboro Stadium outside 
Boston on June 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers also switched around two groups. China originally was  
announced as the top-seeded team in Group C and Norway, the 
defending champion, as the top-seeded team in Group D. But those 
group assignments later were switched, with Norway heading up Group 
C and China leading Group D. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the schedule released weeks ago, the top team in  
Group D is scheduled to play its first match in San Jose and the 
top team in Group C will play its first game at Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said they decided to switch the group assignments  
because they wanted China to play its opener in the San Francisco 
Bay area, which has a large Asian community. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision was made for local marketing reasons by the  
Women's World Cup organizing committee based on the tremendous 
Chinese population in northern California and the interest we 
received from different Chinese organizations to bring the team to 
this venue,'' said Steve Vanderpool, vice president of 
communications for the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The draw was held at halftime of a match won 2-1 by a squad of  
world all-stars against the U.S. national team. Charmaine Hooper of 
Canada scored twice in the second half for the world all-stars. 
Julie Foudy scored the U.S. goal midway through the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. midfielder Michelle Akers left the game in the first half,  
her face bloodied, and was taken to a hospital after bumping heads 
with a world all-star player on a jump ball situation in front of 
the world all-stars' goal. She had a severe cut over her left 
eyebrow and a bruised cheekbone. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatter, head of soccer's world governing body, has said  
repeatedly that ``the future of football is feminine'' and said 
Sunday that female soccer players have a distinct advantage over 
their male counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't cheat. They don't grip the shirt. They don't feign  
a foul,'' Blatter said. ``It's not like the men, who lie on the 
field and are taken off the field on a stretcher and 30 seconds 
later they're running faster than ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's World Cup will have games in or near Boston,  
Chicago, Los Angeles, New York, San Francisco/San Jose, Washington, 
D.C., and Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States won the inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991 in  
China. Norway won the title in 1995 in Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
