<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  3 Designers Take Center Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Three things count in the business of fashion:  
timing, timing, timing. 
</P>
<P>
	That is why American designers are staging their fall Fashion  
Week previews six weeks earlier than usual. 
</P>
<P>
	Fall in February? What's the hurry?  
</P>
<P>
	Ask nearly any designer here: It's good to be the early bird.  
The unprecedented jump-start was prompted by an itch to leapfrog in 
front of the London, Paris and Milan shows. Those fashion capitals 
normally play a gig of openings for an international audience of 
retailers, editors and photographers before sending the weary 
traveling circus packing for the openings here. 
</P>
<P>
	Designers stateside say they want to be judged without being  
compared to the rest of the pack. Besides, they say, having second 
billing typically means receiving more accusations of copying the 
front-runners, having less time for production and delivery, and 
fewer dollars for the U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a slight puffing of the chest, now that Americans can  
compete on a world level and didn't have to be last in the ring of 
shows,'' says Stan Herman, president of 7th on Sixth, which 
coordinates Fashion Week. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the nearly 80 semiannual previews are centralized at  
tents at Bryant Park, a bit of midtown greenery behind the New York 
Public Library. On Monday, fashion fans gathered there to glimpse 
the glamour gowns of Caracas-born Carolina Herrera, celebrated for 
having dressed Hillary Clinton, Jacqueline Kennedy and Whitney 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many occasions, especially in New York, no?''  
says Herrera. That's why she stands ready to lavish her customers 
with pullover sweaters made entirely of mink, dresses fairly 
dripping in ostrich and mohair skirts spangled with sequins. 
</P>
<P>
	But not everything on the runways is for ladies of renown. Or  
for ladies at all. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, both women's and men's shows have been  
consolidated into the Fashion Week schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	At some shows, the runway is coed. Sunday's curtain-raiser, for  
example, was Donna Karan's DKNY line of men's and women's clothes 
built for comfort. DKNY, which runs about 50 percent below the 
price of Donna Karan collection, puts a sporty spin on sportswear. 
</P>
<P>
	For women, there are baggy ``cotton slip cover duvet'' coats,  
which indeed resemble down-filled comforters. For men, the line 
offers hoods, wool cargo pants and drawstrings on nylon pullovers 
to underscore the athletic influence. 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia Rowley, who showed Sunday at Grand Central Terminal, was  
headed for more exotic destinations. ``I have cashmere sweaters 
from Mongolia, sequins from Paris and beading from India,'' she 
said of her embellished women's wear. Even men's snowboard pants 
were teamed with sparkly mohair sweaters. 
</P>
<P>
	But some outfits were sparse, most notably the one worn by  
``Cabaret'' star Alan Cumming, who ended the show bare-chested, in 
a red taffeta ball skirt. He still didn't look quite as fetching as 
front row members Salma Hayek, Jennifer Jason Leigh and Natasha 
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	This season's New York schedule was prompted by German designer  
Helmut Lang. His decision to relocate here and show early during 
last fall's round of Fashion Week created a domino effect, 
inspiring a dozen American designers to likewise jump the gun. 
</P>
<P>
	But not every New York designer is here. Bill Blass and Geoffrey  
Beene are showing in April. Both cite late fabric deliveries. 
Blass' delay also stems from his December hospitalization following 
a mild stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	But in one crucial context, being last has its distinctions:  
This week's previews represent fall 1999/winter 2000 -- the final 
collections of the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	The collections wrap up Friday with Calvin Klein.  
</P>
<P>
	What's next on the fashion roster?  
</P>
<P>
	``With so much change, it is hard to know who is going to  
leapfrog next over whom,'' says Herman. 
</P>
<P>
	He's hardly the only one speculating.  
</P>
<P>
	``In the future,'' says New York designer Randolph Duke, ``we  
may be looking at fashion two years ahead. I could see it 
happening. Like, I could be working now on my collection for 2004 
and saying, `I'm seeing pink.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
