<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Kasich To Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, the chairman of the  
House Budget Committee and a vocal proponent of reducing the 
deficit, has two states in his sights: New Hampshire and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich announced plans to file papers today with the Federal  
Election Commission to formally establish the formation of a 
presidential exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just a little different and a little fresher than a lot of  
the people who are in politics now,'' Kasich, 46, said Sunday on 
NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich joins Sen. John McCain of Arizona, conservative activist  
Gary Bauer, former Vice President Dan Quayle and former Secretary 
of Education Lamar Alexander as Republicans with exploratory 
committees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Early polls and name ID don't mean anything,'' Kasich told the  
television program. ``Politics is ever-changing. I don't worry 
about the polls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ninth-term Republican was scheduled to leave Ohio after a  
breakfast speech today and a rally at Port Columbus International 
Airport. From there he will fly to New Hampshire and Iowa, the 
states that set the primary front-runners. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich described himself as a different kind of Republican  
candidate, one who is not capitalizing on famous relatives or 
personal wealth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a mailman's son from a blue-collar community near  
Pittsburgh,'' Kasich said. ``I got into politics because I wanted 
to change the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich readily admits that he probably won't be able to match  
other candidates' fund-raising skills, but has said he should be 
able to run a credible campaign for less than the $20 million 
believed to be a minimum budget for a national campaign in next 
year's primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	He plans to build recognition and a donor base with the help of  
the Internet, cable television and some offbeat antics, such as a 
bowling alley tour of Iowa later this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	As chairman of the House Budget Committee, Kasich has headed an  
effort to cut $100 billion in spending by 2003, an effort that's 
drawn fire from Democrats and the White House and made many 
Republicans nervous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
