<HEADLINE> Rep. Kasich To Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Talking about tax cuts and Social  
Security, Republican Rep. John Kasich announced the formation a 
presidential exploratory committee Monday before beginning a swing 
through New Hampshire and Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-term congressman announced the formation of Kasich 2000  
at a $100-a-plate breakfast. The step allows him to raise and spend 
campaign money before officially declaring his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to begin to run America from the bottom up. From our  
families, from our communities to the top,'' he told a crowd of 
1,300. ``It's time to take the power back from the elite and put it 
back into the hands of the American people -- into our hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later Monday, he flew to New Hampshire where he told a gathering  
of 70 in Milford that he was a champion of ordinary people, who he 
says can change the world with everyday heroics. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich got his hair cut at Joe's Barber Shop in Milford, and  
asked people to invite him to dinner so he could hear their 
concerns. Barber Joe Swiezynski and a few others said they'd be 
glad to. 
</P>
<P>
	The 46-year-old chairman of the House Budget Committee called  
for improving Social Security and has been pushing for a 10 percent 
tax rate cut that opponents say would disproportionately benefit 
the wealthy. In his speech, Kasich portrays himself as the 
underdog. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to do with the fact that I wasn't born the son of a  
millionaire, and I wasn't born the son of someone who is 
well-connected in society,'' Kasich said at an airport sendoff in 
Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich's swing through New Hampshire, which has the first  
primary, runs through Tuesday, then he is off to Iowa on Thursday 
and Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Others mentioned as potential Republican candidates are former  
Vice President Dan Quayle, former Cabinet secretary Elizabeth Dole, 
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
