<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Trust Unit Suspends Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Shares of a Hong Kong-based subsidiary of a  
troubled Chinese trust were suspended Monday following reports that 
its parent company's finance arm could face liquidation. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Law, company secretary for Gzitic Hualing Holdings Ltd.,  
said Guangzhou Finance has received a court petition for 
liquidation and the hearing will be held April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Guangzhou Finance Co. Ltd. is the finance arm of Gzitic  
Hualing's parent, Guangzhou International Trust and Investment 
Corp., or Gzitic. 
</P>
<P>
	In China, however, a Gzitic executive on Monday denied reports  
that its Hong Kong arm was to be liquidated because of financial 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no problems,'' the executive told Dow Jones  
Newswires on condition of anonymity. No further details were given. 
</P>
<P>
	Guangzhou Finance didn't answer phone calls Monday. Many Hong  
Kong companies were closed Monday for the Lunar New Year, which 
begins Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Law declined to comment on how a liquidation of Guangzhou  
Finance would affect Gzitic Hualing, an investment holding company 
with subsidiaries in the manufacture and sale of household 
electrical appliances. Guangzhou Finance and Gzitic together hold a 
58 percent stake in Gzitic Hualing, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Law said it remains unclear whether Guangzhou Finance will go  
out of business. But the accounting firm KPMG has been appointed by 
Hong Kong's High Court as provisional liquidators, meaning auditors 
from the firm will carry out the liquidation if the court orders 
it, KPMG spokeswoman Pat Lees said. 
</P>
<P>
	The troubles at Gzitic's subsidiaries are the most recent in a  
string of problems that have come to light since the closing of 
Guangdong International Trust and Investment Corp., or Gitic, the 
investment company of China's wealthiest province. 
</P>
<P>
	The government closed Gitic in October, finding the company had  
debts of $4.3 billion and assets of only $2.6 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
