<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed generally lower  
Monday, but the key index in Tokyo rose in reaction to last week's 
government decision to use public funds to support Japan's weakened 
banking system. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 81.03  
points, or 0.58 percent, closing at 14,054.72. On Friday, the index 
rose 21.29 points, or 0.15 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan announced on Friday a plan to inject 7.5  
trillion yen ($66 billion) in public funds into 15 major banks in 
an attempt to prevent Japan's banking system from collapsing. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also got a boost after the central bank said late Friday  
it was cutting a key interest rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan's policy board lowered its target for  
overnight call money -- the rate banks charge each other for 
unsecured short-term loans -- to an all-time low of 0.15 percent 
from 0.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 114.08 yen in late  
afternoon trading, down 0.24 yen from its level Friday in Tokyo and 
also below its New York level of 114.21 yen on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong closed lower in a shortened session,  
with most investors sticking to the sidelines ahead of the Chinese 
New Year holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 23.03 points, or 0.2 percent,  
to 9,402.39. On Friday, the index had surged 278.62 points. The 
bourse closed at midday and will reopen Friday after a three-day 
new year break. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said investors remained cautious ahead of the holiday  
and in the wake of losses on Wall Street Friday and rising local 
interbank rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wall Street was down over 80 points last Friday, and interest  
rates appear to be firming in the U.S. That underlined the bearish 
sentiment,'' said Andrew To, a director at Tai Fook Securities Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower. The NZSE-40  
Capital Index fell 21.82 points, or 1 percent, to 2,147.18. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed lower in quiet trading as most  
investors stayed on the sidelines ahead of the Chinese Lunar New 
Year celebrations. The Philippine Stock Exchange index of 30 
selected companies fell 9.48 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,910.30. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian stock market closed lower. The All  
Ordinaries Index fell 11.7 points, or 0.4 percent, to 2,877.8. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed slightly higher, but volume was  
light ahead of the two-day Chinese New Year holiday. The benchmark 
Straits Times Index rose 6.30 points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,361.15. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed generally mixed, with the key  
index slipping on profit-taking following Friday's 11 percent surge 
that was triggered by the passage of a bill to set up a bankruptcy 
court by the country's senate. The SET index fell 2.47 points, or 
0.7 percent, to 344.96. 
</P>
</TEXT>
