<DOCNO> APW19990215.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 00:51:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Students Find Scholarships Run Dry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- They were, without a doubt, the best and  
brightest high school seniors in the country: straight-A students, 
National Merit Scholars, class valedictorians. 
</P>
<P>
	The students, one from every state in the nation and the  
District of Columbia, each had won a $10,000-a-year college 
scholarship, renewable for four years, from Houston-based 
AdamsVision USA. 
</P>
<P>
	There was just one problem. AdamsVision now admits there is no  
money and never was. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the students are scrambling for financial assistance while  
their parents are searching for answers and, in some cases, 
lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always so trusting. It never even entered my mind that  
something like this could happen,'' said scholarship recipient 
Amber March, who is studying at Eckerd College in Florida. ``I'd 
like to believe it was just an unfortunate mistake, but I kind of 
think I've been had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AdamsVision founder Val Adams insists he still is trying to  
scrape up money to honor the scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very saddened that we're at the point that we are, but at  
the same time I'm very hopeful that we will get these scholarships 
started and be able to continue our commitment,'' Adams said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Boone, a prosecutor with the Harris County district  
attorney's office, doesn't think the students should hold their 
breath. ``Based on my contact with him, I would be concerned if he 
were in any business where anyone was relying on his promises.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boone described Adams as a habitual criminal, convicted of theft  
for writing bogus checks on six different occasions. Adams remains 
on probation for a 1993 case. 
</P>
<P>
	``His schemes were fairly grandiose,'' Boone said. ``He had some  
sort of a fake business and he would use checks from the business 
basically just to live well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boone said Adams may have had legitimate enterprises but that  
``typically there would be no substance behind the business. It 
would just be a front.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adams acknowledges his criminal past but maintains the  
scholarship effort was on the level. He notes that the students 
were not asked to pay an application fee or provide any money, 
something the students and their parents confirm. 
</P>
<P>
	And he insists he invested $300,000 for expenses such as  
salaries for the professional educators who selected the 
recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said he started his company in June 1997 and the  
scholarships were AdamsVision's primary focus. 
</P>
<P>
	In fall 1997, he sent applications for its ``Scholar-Leadership  
Award'' to every high school in the country. An attached letter 
promised the awards would be presented to the winners by the 
governor of their state. 
</P>
<P>
	Eligible students had to have at least a 3.0 grade-point average  
and a combined SAT score of 1160 or above, and submit an essay and 
three letters of recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Lockhart, a former teacher Adams hired as a consultant on  
the project, assembled 15 educators in December 1997 to select the 
winners. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Adams assured her from the start that the scholarship  
money was in place. But Ms. Lockhart became suspicious after Adams, 
despite his contention, failed to pay her and the selection team. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 8, 1998, letters were sent to 51 students announcing  
they had won. But elation turned to confusion a few months later 
when AdamsVision sent another letter saying funding for the 
scholarships wasn't yet complete. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter stated AdamsVision was negotiating with ``two major  
corporations'' regarding sponsorship of the awards presentation and 
that although funding was incomplete, it remained ``absolutely 
confident we will receive corporate sponsorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At that point, however, many students already had accepted early  
placement with universities. Additionally, some had lost out on 
other scholarships after winning one so large. 
</P>
<P>
	``You put one down for $10,000 for four years and you don't get  
anything else,'' said Larry Peters of Little Rock, Ark., whose 
daughter, Jessica, was passed over for another hefty scholarship 
after winning the AdamsVision award. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the final blow. Last month, Adams sent a two-paragraph  
letter to each university stating simply that AdamsVision ``will 
not be financially capable of honoring the Scholar-Leadership Award 
at this time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Adams said he is still trying to get corporations like Sony,  
Ford and Time Warner to bankroll the scholarships. But he 
acknowledges AdamsVision has never received any money from any 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked why he went forward with choosing the scholarship  
recipients when he never had the money in hand, Adams responds: 
``Corporations won't give you money unless we have students. In 
other words, the corporation wants to see what they're buying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several corporations said that was simply false.  
</P>
<P>
	``We want to know after it's awarded, but it's not necessary for  
us to know the recipient prior to us giving the money,'' said 
Graham Painter, a spokesman for Houston-based Reliant Energy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, 51 students have learned a painful lesson about  
trust. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very cheated and very angry,'' said Cassy Marshall of  
Rhinelander, Wis. ``I try not to let it affect me, but it's 
something I can't shake.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 09:56:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Impeach Normalcy Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress is taking a deep breath and then  
diving into what it hopes will be a period of post-impeachment 
normalcy. There's talk of bipartisanship but also real prospects 
for political strife and stalemate. 
</P>
<P>
	After a week off, lawmakers will finally get to concentrate on  
those issues they say they were elected to address -- Social 
Security and Medicare reform, education improvements and tax 
relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are going to have some things to fight about,''  
White House Chief of Staff John Podesta said over the weekend, 
pointing to budget surpluses that Democrats want to use to extend 
the life of Medicare and Republicans want for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The top priority for the Republican majority will be approving  
by sometime in March a budget for fiscal year 2000. Last year, 
Republicans were forced to make major concessions to the 
administration after failing to come up with a budget resolution 
for fiscal year 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	With House Republicans reduced to a six-seat majority, new  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised to work with 
Democrats, and says he and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., want to meet President Clinton to look for areas of 
agreement. ``If we are going to do anything at all and be 
productive then we have to work with the president,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the first order of business, approving a budget, will be an  
exercise in dismantling Clinton's $1.77 trillion proposal by 
attacking his plan for saving Social Security and promoting GOP tax 
cut ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, the Senate GOP policy committee  
chairman, said there will be ``some bipartisan flavor'' to bills 
coming out of Congress, but with Clinton's impeachment trial over, 
``we ought to walk away from him and move with our agenda as if 
Bill Clinton never existed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House, which finished its role in the trial last year, has  
already gotten off to a fairly conventional start, holding Social 
Security and budget hearings and passing legislation intended to 
shield businesses from federal laws and regulations that companies 
say add to their costs of operating. 
</P>
<P>
	But with the end of the trial, the Senate will for the first  
time this year get a shot at voting on legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said that among the first items to come up will be a  
popular measure to boost military pay and two more complex issues -- 
building a missile defense system and giving local authorities 
greater control over the spending of education dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	He called the creation of a missile defense system ``crucial,''  
adding: ``The bad news is we do not have one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration and many Democrats support the basic concepts  
of the missile and education bills, but are certain to fight over 
the details. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., said he would try to amend the  
education bill to deny money to localities that promote children 
who don't meet basic standards and to seek more money for Clinton's 
plan for an additional 100,000 elementary school teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will renew the fight for things that make a difference in  
people's lives, starting with urging needed reforms in HMOs, aid 
for school construction repairs and an increase in the minimum 
wage,'' Kennedy said. 
</P>
<P>
	House members introduced a similar education bill last week and  
stood by their approach to decentralized authority. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will give the local schools the flexibility to spend  
federal education dollars as they see fit,'' said Rep. John 
Peterson, R-Pa. ``It's an approach that will enrage the liberals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first bills to reach the House floor will be a  
measure to protect cellphone users from electronic eavesdropping. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other measures sure to raise serious political sparks  
are also headed for early spring consideration: 
</P>
<P>
	--Congress will try again to establish a temporary nuclear waste  
storage site in Nevada. Nevada's senators, backed by the 
administration, have successfully filibustered the bill the last 
few years. 
</P>
<P>
	--The business community is pushing legislation that would  
protect businesses from costly lawsuits resulting from computer 
problems in the year 2000. Trial lawyers say the bill would give 
businesses an excuse for not fixing the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	--New Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, has  
promised to give priority to legislation to break down regulatory 
barriers between financial institutions. The bill passed the House 
by only one vote last year; Gramm's opposition to provisions 
requiring banks to lend to the poor and minorities in their 
neighborhoods prevented Senate action. 
</P>
<P>
	--The administration supports legislation aimed at promoting  
trade with sub-Saharan Africa through lower tariffs, but some 
Democrats want to expand the bill to include debt relief for those 
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
