<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 03:45:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It was mainly dry across most of the country this morning,  
although light snow was falling in parts of Montana and eastern 
Idaho. Rain or snow was expected to move into the Plains tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry weather was predicted in the East, with mostly  
clear skies. Temperatures are expected to rebound from their 
seasonably cold levels in New England and the Southeast as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloudiness may be widespread across northern and central areas  
of the Plains today as a storm system moves out of the central and 
northern Rockies. Snow could develop in the western Dakotas early 
today and spread into eastern areas of these states and into 
western Nebraska and Kansas tonight. Accumulations are expected to 
be light, but winds may be quite strong across these areas with low 
visibilities and minor drifting of snow. 
</P>
<P>
	Precipitation in the form of showers and thunderstorms are  
forecast in western Oklahoma and northern Texas late today as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Light snow may continue in eastern Montana and also be seen in  
eastern Wyoming this afternoon. More significant snow could develop 
in the higher elevations of central Colorado late tonight. Another 
storm system is expected to enter western areas of Washington, 
Oregon and northwestern California this afternoon. Rain is expected 
in the lower elevations with snow above 1,500 feet in some areas. 
Accompanying winds could reach 50 mph along the Oregon and 
Washington coasts. The remainder of the northern portions of the 
West may see mostly cloudy skies with mostly clear skies in the 
desert Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast temperature highs: in the 30s and 40s in the  
Pacific Northwest, the northern Plains and the Northeast; in the 
50s and 60s in the mid-Atlantic states, the central and southern 
Plains, California, the Southwest and the Southeast; and in the 70s 
in south Florida, southern Texas and southern California near the 
U.S.-Mexico border. 
</P>
<P>
	The extreme temperatures in the U.S. mainland Sunday were 69 in  
Homestead, Fla. and minus 9 in Saranac Lake, N.Y. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
