all over the world,'' said Donna de Varona, chair of the organizing 
committee for the 32-match tournament that will run from June 
19-July 10 in seven U.S. cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States drew North Korea, Nigeria and Denmark in its  
group for first-round matches. The Americans have six wins and a 
tie in their 10 games against Denmark, while the U.S. squad has 
never played North Korea or Nigeria. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could call this the unknown group, because we really don't  
know North Korea or Nigeria very well,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco 
said after Sunday night's draw. ``Denmark has been a strong, 
physical opponent for us in the past, and will be a good test for 
us in the opener.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffeny Milbrett, a forward on the U.S. team, said the Americans  
are more comfortable with Denmark than with the other nations in 
their group. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I am a little scared of unknown teams,'' Milbrett  
said. ``Often those types of teams are scrappy teams. And scrappy 
teams' strengths tend to match up against our weaknesses pretty 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draw resulted in confusion about which nation the Americans  
will play in their opening match, and got more confusing when 
officials switched around two groups for marketing reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	FIFA president Sepp Blatter announced during the draw ceremony,  
televised live throughout the United States, that the U.S. team 
will face North Korea in its opening match June 19 at Giants 
Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	But Women's World Cup officials later said the U.S. team will  
face Denmark in that opening match. The Americans will play Nigeria 
at Chicago's Soldier Field on June 24 and complete their 
first-round matches against North Korea at Foxboro Stadium outside 
Boston on June 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers also switched around two groups. China originally was  
announced as the top-seeded team in Group C and Norway, the 
defending champion, as the top-seeded team in Group D. But those 
group assignments later were switched, with Norway heading up Group 
C and China leading Group D. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the schedule released weeks ago, the top team in  
Group D is scheduled to play its first match in San Jose and the 
top team in Group C will play its first game at Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers said they decided to switch the group assignments  
because they wanted China to play its opener in the San Francisco 
Bay area, which has a large Asian community. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision was made for local marketing reasons by the  
Women's World Cup organizing committee based on the tremendous 
Chinese population in northern California and the interest we 
received from different Chinese organizations to bring the team to 
this venue,'' said Steve Vanderpool, vice president of 
communications for the Women's World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The draw was held at halftime of a match won 2-1 by a squad of  
world all-stars against the U.S. national team. Charmaine Hooper of 
Canada scored twice in the second half for the world all-stars. 
Julie Foudy scored the U.S. goal midway through the first half. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. midfielder Michelle Akers left the game in the first half,  
her face bloodied, and was taken to a hospital after bumping heads 
with a world all-star player on a jump ball situation in front of 
the world all-stars' goal. She had a severe cut over her left 
eyebrow and a bruised cheekbone. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatter, head of soccer's world governing body, has said  
repeatedly that ``the future of football is feminine'' and said 
Sunday that female soccer players have a distinct advantage over 
their male counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't cheat. They don't grip the shirt. They don't feign  
a foul,'' Blatter said. ``It's not like the men, who lie on the 
field and are taken off the field on a stretcher and 30 seconds 
later they're running faster than ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's World Cup will have games in or near Boston,  
Chicago, Los Angeles, New York, San Francisco/San Jose, Washington, 
D.C., and Portland, Ore. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States won the inaugural Women's World Cup in 1991 in  
China. Norway won the title in 1995 in Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990215.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 09:56:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Samsung Still Committed to Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Despite the Salt Lake City's Olympic  
corruption scandal, Samsung Electronics Co. said Monday it won't 
abandon its $45 million sponsorship of the 2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are worried the commercial values of the Olympics have  
suffered because of these scandals,'' spokeswoman Cho Sung-in said. 
``But we remain committed to our sponsorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cho spoke in reaction to an Australian newspaper report that  
Samsung's sponsorship was in doubt because of vote-buying scandals 
and other allegations of misconduct involving members of the 
International Olympic Committee. Cho said The Sydney Morning Herald 
report Monday was ``far too exaggerating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Se-hun, Samsung Electronics' sports marketing senior  
manager, was quoted as saying, ``We believe the recent scandals 
present some danger to sponsorship. We still need to evaluate the 
reports of the various judiciary committees before making decisions 
or definite comments as to the next step.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cho said that while Samsung was ``carefully watching the  
investigation,'' the company ``never said we will withdraw our 
sponsorship. We are investing for the Sydney Olympics as 
scheduled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney 2000 organizing president Michael Knight also discounted  
the newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samsung are absolutely committed to the Sydney 2000  
Olympics,'' Knight said. ``Indeed, I'm having dinner tonight with 
some of the Samsung people who have paid $5,200 as a donation to 
the Australian Olympic team fundraiser to have dinner with myself 
and some of the athletes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A major Olympic partner, John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co ,  
criticized the IOC last week and said it will not use the Olympic 
rings as part of marketing programs until corruption is purged. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight said Monday he thought no sponsors would pull out of  
Olympic deals and said additional agreements will be announced 
within the next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydney organizers are seeking about $130 million to reach their  
sponsorship target for the 2000 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Samsung became a worldwide partner of the Olympics in 1997 and  
its chairman, Lee Kun-hee, has been an IOC member since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
