<DOCNO> APW19990215.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-15 10:43:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How the Media Survived Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Kathleen Hall Jamieson was shocked to open her  
newspaper the other day and find something other than Monica 
Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Shocked, but pleased.  
</P>
<P>
	``What would it take to displace the non-news of  
Clinton-Lewinsky from the front page? The answer was King 
Hussein,'' said Ms. Jamieson, dean of the University of 
Pennsylvania's Annenberg School of Communication. 
</P>
<P>
	To Ms. Jamieson's mind, too much has been written and broadcast  
over the past year about oral sex in the Oval Office, crowding out 
other stories that should have drawn attention -- the surplus and 
Social Security, education and patients' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	She's not alone. From the beginning, the news media have been  
pilloried for Clinton-Lewinsky overkill. They have been criticized 
for inaccuracies, and for reliance on unidentified, manipulative 
sources. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, more than a year and untold amounts of ink later, the  
unending story has reached an end -- at least for the moment. 
</P>
<P>
	And the question remains: How did the press do?  
</P>
<P>
	The answer, according to critics: OK -- with some exceptions. And  
it wasn't a pretty thing to watch, regardless. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the mainstream press ... did under the circumstances a  
superior job, and they were also self-correcting,'' said Gene 
Roberts, a former top editor at The New York Times and Philadelphia 
Inquirer and now a professor at the University of Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	``When someone made a mistake, there were so many people working  
on the story that immediately, it was pointed out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two largest mistakes were made early on, when The Dallas  
Morning News and The Wall Street Journal retracted reports on their 
Web pages that third parties had seen President Clinton and Miss 
Lewinsky alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two instances across a year are not that bad,'' Ms. Jamieson  
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	Some organizations were especially careful. Tom Rosenstiel,  
media critic and director of the Project for Excellence in 
Journalism, said the Los Angeles Times had the story of Ms. 
Lewinsky's stained blue dress, but, ``They decided that it did not 
meet their standards'' for corroboration. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC went with the story, based on a single source, Rosenstiel  
said -- and it was true. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenstiel said there was a ``seller's market'' for information  
-- a market in which the media were open to manipulation by 
anonymous sources. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a cascade of single-source stories in the frenzy at  
the story's start, and then in those periods when little was 
happening, and much of the media felt the need to report something 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``The low point of the story was the trough between late  
February and the end of July-August, when the walls started 
tumbling around Clinton's denials,'' said James Poniewozik, media 
columnist for Salon, the Web magazine. ``There was a numbing cycle 
of opinion and speculation and conjecture going on for five or six 
months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the leaks turned out to be true, but the news came out  
in dribs and drabs, and it left the public confused. 
</P>
<P>
	``People got sick of the story. They wanted it to go away,  
because they couldn't evaluate whether it was true or not,'' said 
Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public 
Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The perception, Lichter said, was that these unending  
disclosures were unfair to Clinton, so sympathy drifted his way. 
When Clinton's presidency was imperiled, public opinion stayed 
firmly on his side. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a cadre of commentators took up residence on cable  
news channels, adding ``heat and no light'' to the story, Roberts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wonder what these people are going to do when the story is  
over,'' he said. ``I never saw them before this, and I don't 
particularly want to see them again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From the start, the media's focus on the story flew in the face  
of the public's distaste for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normally, the press does a pretty good job of having their ear  
to the ground and hearing it the way people are saying it. This is 
a case where the national press haven't been hearing what the folks 
are saying,'' said Roderick P. Hart, a professor of communication 
and government at the University of Texas at Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rosenstiel said, ``Our instincts told us that this was an  
important story. But the public told us early on that they didn't 
think so. ... We hoped our instincts would be vindicated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually it happened, but ``it still antagonized a lot of  
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roberts said that he came ``from a time when newspapers didn't  
get into sex, or did only if somebody jumped into the reflecting 
pool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he can't imagine the media laying off a story like this  
one: ``I think if people are talking about impeaching the 
president, it seems to me you have some obligation to cover it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
